const a = [
  {"id":1812,"text":"While examining the lateral view of the X-ray of the skull, a radiologist points out a region that is the meeting point of the parietomastoid, occipitomastoid, and lambdoid sutures. What point is he referring to?","explanation":"The **asterion** is an anatomical landmark located at the junction of the parietomastoid, occipitomastoid, and lambdoid sutures. It is situated in the temporal region of the skull, typically at the level of the asterion.\r\n\r\nIdentifying the asterion is important for various clinical purposes, including neurosurgery, radiology, and anatomical localization. For example, it serves as a reference point for the placement of burr holes during surgical procedures and is also used in cranial measurements and radiographic interpretation.","reference":"Chung KW, Chung HM, Halliday NL. BRS: Gross Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer Health; 2015: 369.","responses":[{"text":"Inion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lambda","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bregma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asterion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1992,"text":"The rhombencephalic isthmus separates which parts of the brain?","explanation":"The **rhombencephalic isthmus** separates the **mesencephalon** from the **metencephalon** during embryonic development.\r\n\r\nThe rhombencephalon is the hindbrain, which further divides into the metencephalon and the myelencephalon. The mesencephalon, also known as the midbrain, is the region above the rhombencephalic isthmus.\r\n\r\nThe rhombencephalic isthmus plays a crucial role in the development and differentiation of the brain structures. It serves as a signaling center and generates important molecular signals that influence the fate and patterning of adjacent brain regions. These signals guide the development of specific neuronal populations and the formation of various brain structures.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 313.","responses":[{"text":"Mesencephalon from the metencephalon","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myelencephalon from the spinal cord","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rhombencephalon from the mesencephalon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metencephalon from the myelencephalon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prosencephalon from the diencephalon","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2091,"text":"Where does the aqueous humor drain into?","explanation":"The **aqueous humor** in the eye drains into the **scleral venous sinus**, also known as the **canal of Schlemm**.\r\n\r\nThe aqueous humor is a clear fluid that is produced by the ciliary body in the posterior chamber of the eye. It nourishes and maintains the shape of the anterior segment of the eye, which includes the cornea and the lens.\r\n\r\nAfter circulating through the anterior chamber, the aqueous humor drains into the scleral venous sinus, which is located at the junction of the cornea and the sclera. The scleral venous sinus acts as a drainage system, allowing the aqueous humor to exit the eye and return to the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nProper drainage of the aqueous humor is important for maintaining the intraocular pressure within a normal range. Disruption of the drainage pathways can lead to increased intraocular pressure, a condition known as glaucoma.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 905.","responses":[{"text":"Scleral venous sinus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sigmoidal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ethmoidal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cavernous sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sagittal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2114,"text":"The gland that secretes calcitonin is formed from which pharyngeal pouch?","explanation":"The gland that secretes calcitonin, known as the **thyroid gland**, is formed from the **4th pharyngeal pouch** during embryonic development.\r\n\r\nDuring early development, the pharyngeal arches and pouches play a crucial role in the formation of various structures in the head and neck region. The thyroid gland originates from the endodermal cells of the **floor of the 4th pharyngeal pouch**. These cells migrate downward and fuse in the midline to form the primordial thyroid gland.\r\n\r\nThe thyroid gland is responsible for the production and secretion of various hormones, including calcitonin. Calcitonin plays a role in regulating calcium and phosphate metabolism in the body.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 163-164.","responses":[{"text":"5th","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1st","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4th","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"2nd","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2121,"text":"Which of the following ions moves from endolymph to stereocilia to depolarize the hair cells?","explanation":"The ion that moves from the endolymph to the stereocilia of hair cells to depolarize them is **K+ (potassium ion)**.\r\n\r\nIn the inner ear, the sensory hair cells of the cochlea and vestibular system are responsible for converting mechanical vibrations into electrical signals that can be interpreted by the brain. This process involves the movement of ions, specifically potassium, to initiate depolarization and signal transmission.\r\n\r\nThe endolymph, which is the fluid within the cochlear and vestibular ducts, has a high concentration of potassium ions. When sound vibrations or head movements stimulate the stereocilia of the hair cells, the mechanotransduction channels open, allowing potassium ions to flow into the hair cells. This influx of potassium depolarizes the hair cells and triggers the release of neurotransmitters, initiating the transmission of auditory or balance signals to the brain.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 668.","responses":[{"text":"K+","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mg2+","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cl-","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ca2+","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Na+","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2198,"text":"Sensory retina develops from which part of the optic cup?","explanation":"The sensory retina develops from the **Pars optica retinae** of the optic cup.\r\n\r\nDuring embryonic development, the optic cup forms from the optic vesicle, which is an outpouching of the neural tube. The optic cup consists of two layers: the outer pigmented layer and the inner neural layer. The inner neural layer of the optic cup differentiates into the sensory retina.\r\n\r\nThe Pars optica retinae, also known as the optic cup proper, refers to the anterior portion of the neural layer of the optic cup. This region gives rise to the sensory retina, which contains the photoreceptor cells (rods and cones) responsible for detecting light and initiating the visual signaling process.\r\n\r\nThe sensory retina plays a critical role in vision by capturing and processing visual stimuli before transmitting them to the brain via the optic nerve.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 362.","responses":[{"text":"Pars optica retinae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars caeca retinae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars iridica retinae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pars ciliaris retinae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Outer layer of the optic cup","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2235,"text":"Pterygoid venous plexus is a network of veins that drains into which of the following vein?","explanation":"The pterygoid venous plexus is a network of veins that drains into the **maxillary vein**.\r\n\r\nThe pterygoid venous plexus is located in the pterygopalatine fossa, which is a small space in the skull behind the maxilla and lateral to the nasal cavity. It is formed by an intricate network of veins that communicate with each other and receive blood from various regions of the face and cranial cavity.\r\n\r\nThe veins of the pterygoid venous plexus drain into multiple venous channels, one of which is the **maxillary vein**. The maxillary vein is a major vein that accompanies the maxillary artery in the infratemporal fossa. It receives blood from the pterygoid venous plexus, as well as other veins in the region, and ultimately contributes to the venous drainage of the face.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1107.","responses":[{"text":"Maxillary vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cavernous sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior ophthalmic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior ophthalmic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2254,"text":"The swallowing center is located in which of the following?","explanation":"The swallowing center is located in the **medulla oblongata**.\r\n\r\nThe medulla oblongata is the lowest part of the brainstem, connecting the brain to the spinal cord. It plays a crucial role in controlling many vital functions, including respiration, blood pressure regulation, and swallowing.\r\n\r\nWithin the medulla oblongata, there is a specialized region called the **swallowing center**. This center coordinates the complex series of muscle contractions and movements involved in the process of swallowing, also known as deglutition. The swallowing center receives sensory input from various sources, including the oral cavity and pharynx, and coordinates the sequential activation of the muscles involved in swallowing.\r\n\r\nDamage or dysfunction of the swallowing center in the medulla can lead to swallowing difficulties, known as dysphagia.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 798.","responses":[{"text":"Pons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebellum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medulla oblongata","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Midbrain","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2270,"text":"Taste fibres from circumvallate papillae pass through what nerve?","explanation":"Taste fibers from the circumvallate papillae pass through the **glossopharyngeal nerve**.\r\n\r\nThe glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) is a cranial nerve responsible for transmitting sensory information from the posterior third of the tongue, including the taste buds located on the circumvallate papillae. These large papillae are situated at the back of the tongue in a V-shaped row.\r\n\r\nTaste information from the circumvallate papillae is carried by the glossopharyngeal nerve fibers to the **solitary nucleus** in the medulla oblongata, where it is processed and integrated with other sensory inputs related to taste. From there, taste signals are further relayed to other regions of the brain for perception and interpretation.","reference":"Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 13th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 687.","responses":[{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chorda tympani","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2275,"text":"Which is not present in the carotid sheath?","explanation":"The **external jugular vein** is not present in the carotid sheath.\r\n\r\nThe carotid sheath is a fibrous connective tissue sheath that contains important structures in the neck. It is located on the lateral aspect of the neck and extends from the base of the skull to the superior mediastinum. The structures that are typically found within the carotid sheath include the **internal carotid artery**, **internal jugular vein**, and **vagus nerve**.\r\n\r\nThe internal carotid artery is a major blood vessel that supplies blood to the brain. It travels through the carotid sheath alongside the internal jugular vein, which is responsible for draining deoxygenated blood from the brain, face, and neck. The vagus nerve, also known as the tenth cranial nerve, is a mixed nerve that carries motor and sensory fibers to various organs in the neck, thorax, and abdomen.\r\n\r\nThe external jugular vein, on the other hand, is not located within the carotid sheath. It is a superficial vein that is visible on the lateral surface of the neck and drains blood from the scalp and face.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 997.","responses":[{"text":"Internal carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal jugular vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External jugular vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Common carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2305,"text":"Which muscle takes part in the formation of palatine aponeurosis?","explanation":"The **tensor veli palatini** muscle takes part in the formation of the palatine aponeurosis.\r\n\r\nThe palatine aponeurosis is a thin, fibrous sheet that extends horizontally across the posterior part of the hard palate. It plays a role in elevating the soft palate and closing off the nasopharynx during swallowing and speaking. The palatine aponeurosis is an important structure in maintaining the integrity of the soft palate and its proper functioning.\r\n\r\nThe tensor veli palatini muscle is one of the muscles involved in the soft palate's movement and function. It arises from the cartilaginous part of the auditory tube (eustachian tube) and the adjacent sphenoid bone. It courses downward and laterally to insert into the palatine aponeurosis. Contraction of the tensor veli palatini muscle helps to tense and flatten the soft palate, contributing to the closure of the nasopharynx during swallowing and speaking.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 946.","responses":[{"text":"Musculus uvulae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tensor veli palatini","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tensor tympani","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatoglossus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatopharyngeus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2494,"text":"Which of the following equalizes the pressure between the external atmosphere and the middle ear cavity?","explanation":"The **Eustachian tube** (also known as the auditory tube or pharyngotympanic tube) is responsible for equalizing the pressure between the external atmosphere and the middle ear cavity.\r\n\r\nThe Eustachian tube connects the middle ear cavity to the nasopharynx (the back of the throat). Its primary function is to regulate pressure in the middle ear, allowing the equalization of air pressure on both sides of the tympanic membrane (eardrum). \r\n\r\nDuring activities such as swallowing, yawning, or chewing, the Eustachian tube opens briefly, allowing air to flow in or out of the middle ear. This equalizes the pressure between the middle ear and the external atmosphere, preventing discomfort or distortion of sound perception. It also helps in maintaining the optimal functioning of the middle ear, including the movement of the ossicles (small bones) and transmission of sound vibrations.\r\n\r\nDysfunction or blockage of the Eustachian tube can lead to a feeling of ear fullness, muffled hearing, or even pain.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 946.","responses":[{"text":"Eustachian tube","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Auricle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tympanic membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pinna","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2495,"text":"What happens to the vocal cords while swallowing?","explanation":"During swallowing, the vocal cords undergo a specific movement known as **approximation**. \r\n\r\nThe vocal cords, which are located within the larynx, play a crucial role in phonation (production of sound) and preventing the entry of food or liquid into the airway. When swallowing occurs, the vocal cords are brought together and tightly closed to form a protective barrier. This prevents the entry of food or liquid into the lower respiratory tract, ensuring that they pass down the esophagus instead.\r\n\r\nThe process of approximation is coordinated by the muscles of the larynx, particularly the **lateral cricoarytenoid muscles**. These muscles contract during swallowing, causing the vocal cords to move medially and come into contact with each other. This closure helps to seal off the entrance to the airway, maintaining airway protection during the swallowing process.\r\n\r\nOnce the swallowing is complete, the vocal cords return to their resting position and resume their role in vocalization.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 798.","responses":[{"text":"Opened","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gapped by membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Approximated","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"No change","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Overlapped","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2497,"text":"A teacher discussed a fossa inferior and deep to the zygomatic arch and posterior to the maxilla. The appropriate fossa being discussed is?","explanation":"The **infratemporal fossa** is a complex anatomical region located deep within the skull, adjacent to the temporal bone. It is bordered by the zygomatic arch anteriorly, the maxilla and lateral pterygoid plate medially, the styloid process and mastoid process posteriorly, and the ramus of the mandible inferiorly. \r\n\r\nThis fossa contains various important structures, including the **mandibular nerve (branch of the trigeminal nerve)**, the **maxillary artery**, the **pterygoid muscles**, and the **inferior part of the temporalis muscle**. It serves as a conduit for the passage of neurovascular structures and plays a role in mastication (chewing) and jaw movement.","reference":"1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 826.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n2) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 925.","responses":[{"text":"Pterygopalatine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occipital","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle cranial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infratemporal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2511,"text":"Which nucleus of the thalamus is responsible for carrying fibers to the auditory cortex?","explanation":"The nucleus of the thalamus that is responsible for carrying fibers to the auditory cortex is the **medial geniculate body**.\r\n\r\nThe auditory pathway involves the transmission of auditory information from the cochlea to the auditory cortex in the brain. After auditory signals are received by the cochlea, they are relayed through the cochlear nuclei in the brainstem. From there, the fibers ascend to the **medial geniculate body** located in the thalamus.\r\n\r\nThe medial geniculate body acts as a relay station for auditory information. It receives fibers from the cochlear nuclei and then projects these fibers to the auditory cortex, which is located in the temporal lobe of the brain. This pathway allows for the processing and interpretation of sound signals, contributing to our perception of hearing.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 669.","responses":[{"text":"Venteroposterolateral nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dorsomedial nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventroposteromedial nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral geniculate body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial geniculate body","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2535,"text":"Which of the following structures is a content of the pterygopalatine fossa?","explanation":"One of the structures that is a content of the pterygopalatine fossa is the **3rd part of the maxillary artery**.\r\n\r\nThe pterygopalatine fossa is a small space located deep within the skull, behind the maxilla and lateral to the nasal cavity. It serves as a crossroads for several important structures. One of these structures is the maxillary artery, which is a major branch of the external carotid artery. The maxillary artery enters the pterygopalatine fossa and passes through its 3rd part before continuing on to supply various structures in the face and oral cavity.\r\n\r\nThe 3rd part of the maxillary artery gives off several branches within the pterygopalatine fossa, including the posterior superior alveolar artery, infraorbital artery, and descending palatine artery. These branches contribute to the blood supply of the teeth, gums, palate, and other structures in the region.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 983.","responses":[{"text":"3rd part of the maxillary artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infraorbital nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2nd part of maxillary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Otic ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1st part of the maxillary artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9403,"text":"What is the position of the macula lutea relative to the optic disc in the eyeball?","explanation":"The **macula lutea** is located **lateral** to the optic disc in the eyeball.\r\n\r\nThe macula lutea is a small, oval-shaped area located in the central part of the retina. It is responsible for central vision and contains a high concentration of cone cells, which are specialized photoreceptor cells for color vision and visual acuity. The macula lutea is slightly **lateral** to the optic disc.\r\n\r\nThe optic disc, also known as the blind spot, is the site where the optic nerve exits the eye and contains no photoreceptor cells. It is located on the **medial** side of the posterior pole of the eyeball. The macula lutea is situated slightly **lateral** to the optic disc, closer to the temporal side of the eyeball.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 905.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9408,"text":"Anesthesia in retromolar fossa primarily blocks which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The **retromolar fossa** is a triangular depression located behind the last molar tooth in the mandible. Anesthesia in this region primarily blocks the **buccal nerve**, which is a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V). The buccal nerve provides sensory innervation to the buccal mucosa, skin of the cheek, and the mucous membrane of the lower lip.\r\n\r\nBlocking the buccal nerve can be achieved through local anesthesia techniques, such as an inferior alveolar nerve block or an infiltration technique, to provide pain relief and numbness in the retromolar fossa and surrounding areas.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 870.","responses":[{"text":"Mental nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior alveolar nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9410,"text":"Fracture of mandible most likely results in the damage of which of the following nerves?","explanation":"The **inferior alveolar nerve** is a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V3). It provides sensory innervation to the lower teeth, lower lip, and chin. \r\n\r\nA fracture of the mandible, particularly in the region of the body or angle, can potentially damage the inferior alveolar nerve. This can occur due to direct trauma or compression of the nerve by displaced bone fragments. The resulting injury to the nerve can lead to numbness or altered sensation in the areas it supplies.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 939.","responses":[{"text":"Lingual nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior alveolar nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9631,"text":"A patient comes to the outpatient department with complaints of dryness of nose and palate. Which ganglion must be damaged?","explanation":"When a patient presents with symptoms of dryness in the nose and palate, the **pterygopalatine ganglion** is a likely site of damage. The pterygopalatine ganglion, also known as the **sphenopalatine ganglion**, is a parasympathetic ganglion located in the pterygopalatine fossa.\r\n\r\nThe pterygopalatine ganglion is responsible for innervating various structures in the head and neck, including the nasal mucosa and the palatal glands. It receives preganglionic parasympathetic fibers from the facial nerve (CN VII) via the **greater petrosal nerve** and the **nerve of the pterygoid canal**.\r\n\r\nThe postganglionic parasympathetic fibers from the pterygopalatine ganglion travel to the nasal mucosa, where they stimulate **mucous glands** and promote the secretion of mucus. Additionally, these fibers also innervate the **palatal glands**, which are responsible for producing saliva and maintaining moisture in the palate.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 986.","responses":[{"text":"Pterygopalatine ganglion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Otic ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nodose ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciliary ganglion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9632,"text":"Which type of gland is the gland of Zeis?","explanation":"The **gland of Zeis** is a type of **modified sebaceous gland** located in the eyelids. It is named after the Swiss anatomist Johann Gottfried Zeis, who first described these glands.\r\n\r\nSebaceous glands are typically found throughout the body and are responsible for producing sebum, an oily substance that helps lubricate and protect the skin and hair. In the case of the gland of Zeis, it is specifically associated with the eyelashes.\r\n\r\nThe gland of Zeis is located in the **dermis** of the eyelid, near the base of the eyelash follicle. Its primary function is to secrete **sebum** onto the base of the eyelash, helping to keep the eyelash and the surrounding skin moisturized and lubricated.\r\n\r\nThe secretion of sebum from the gland of Zeis helps prevent the eyelashes from becoming dry and brittle. It also plays a role in preventing the eyelashes from sticking together and promotes their flexibility.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 252.","responses":[{"text":"Mucus glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified lacrimal glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified sebaceous glands","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mebomian glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified sweat glands","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9658,"text":"Which of the following is true about the canal of Schlemm?","explanation":"The **canal of Schlemm**, also known as the **scleral venous sinus**, is an important structure located in the anterior chamber of the eye. It plays a crucial role in regulating the outflow of aqueous humor, which is important for maintaining intraocular pressure. \r\n\r\nOne of the true characteristics of the canal of Schlemm is that it is **lined by endothelium**. The endothelial cells form the inner lining of the canal and create a barrier between the aqueous humor and the surrounding tissues. The endothelium of the canal of Schlemm is composed of specialized cells that are responsible for the reabsorption of aqueous humor from the anterior chamber into the bloodstream.\r\n\r\nThe canal of Schlemm does not contain red blood cells, as it primarily serves as a drainage pathway for aqueous humor rather than blood. Additionally, it does not directly communicate with the vitreous chamber, as the aqueous humor flows through the anterior chamber and exits the eye through the canal of Schlemm and the venous system.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 246.","responses":[{"text":"It is lined by stratified squamous epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is lined by endothelium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It contains red cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It communicates with the vitreous chamber","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11194,"text":"Ethmoidal bulla can be seen in the middle nasal meatus. Which of the following is related to ethmoidal bulla?","explanation":"The ethmoidal bulla is related to the **middle ethmoidal sinus**. The ethmoidal sinuses are air-filled spaces located within the ethmoid bone, situated between the eyes and medial to the orbits. The middle ethmoidal sinus is one of the three main subdivisions of the ethmoidal sinuses.\r\n\r\nThe ethmoidal bulla is a rounded prominence or bulge that arises from the lateral wall of the middle nasal meatus. It represents the most anterior and largest part of the middle ethmoidal sinus. The bulla helps to define the boundaries of the middle ethmoidal sinus and contributes to the drainage of its contents.\r\n\r\nThe ethmoidal bulla is an important landmark during nasal endoscopic procedures and sinus surgeries. Its position and size can vary among individuals, and it plays a role in determining the anatomy and drainage patterns of the middle ethmoidal sinus.","reference":"Drake RL, Vogl W, Mitchell AWM, Gray H. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 3rd ed. Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2015: 1073.","responses":[{"text":"Inferior ethmoidal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle ethmoidal sinus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Frontal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior ethmoidal sinus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11803,"text":"Nasolacrimal duct drains tears to which of the following parts of the nose?","explanation":"Tears are produced by the lacrimal glands and help keep the surface of the eyes moist and protected. Excess tears and fluid drain through the lacrimal puncta, which are small openings located at the inner corner of the eye. From there, tears flow into the lacrimal canaliculi and then into the lacrimal sac. Finally, the nasolacrimal duct connects the lacrimal sac to the **inferior nasal meatus**, which is located in the nasal cavity.\r\n\r\nBy draining into the inferior nasal meatus, tears are able to mix with the nasal secretions and eventually reach the back of the throat, without causing excessive watering or overflow of tears.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 901.","responses":[{"text":"Superior nasal meatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lacrimal sac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle nasal meatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior nasal conchae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior nasal meatus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13017,"text":"Which of the following structures is present on the medial wall of the middle ear?","explanation":"The **oval window**, also known as the **fenestra vestibuli**, is a membrane-covered opening that connects the middle ear to the vestibule of the inner ear. It is located just below the prominence of the **pyramidal process**, which is a small bony ridge in the medial wall. The **tympanic membrane**, also known as the eardrum, separates the external ear from the middle ear and is adjacent to the medial wall. \r\n\r\nThe **epitympanic recess** is located on the superior portion of the middle ear, while the **Eustachian tube** connects the middle ear to the nasopharynx and is situated in the anterior wall.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 949.","responses":[{"text":"Eustachian tube","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oval window","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tympanic membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epitympanic recess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyramidal process","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13019,"text":"Which of the following is not present on the lateral wall of the middle ear?","explanation":"The lateral wall of the middle ear consists of several important structures that contribute to its function. These include the **epitympanic recess**, which is a small space located above the tympanic membrane. The **handle of the malleus** (also known as the **manubrium**) is a long process of the malleus bone that is attached to the tympanic membrane, transmitting sound vibrations to the inner ear. The **attachment of the tensor tympani muscle** is also located on the lateral wall, and this muscle is involved in dampening the movement of the ossicles to protect the inner ear from loud sounds. \r\n\r\nHowever, the **round window** is not present on the lateral wall of the middle ear. Instead, it is located on the **medial wall** of the middle ear, adjacent to the cochlea. The round window plays a crucial role in equalizing pressure and facilitating the movement of fluid within the cochlea.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 948, 950.","responses":[{"text":"Round window","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Epitympanic recess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Handle of malleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chorda tympani","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Attachment of tensor tympani","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13020,"text":"Which muscle is not supplied by the hypoglossal nerve?","explanation":"The **hypoglossal nerve** primarily innervates the muscles of the tongue and is responsible for their motor function. It supplies the intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue, except for the palatoglossus muscle.\r\n\r\nThe **palatoglossus muscle**, on the other hand, is innervated by the **vagus nerve** (cranial nerve X), specifically by its pharyngeal branch. The palatoglossus muscle forms part of the **palatopharyngeal arch** and is involved in swallowing and elevating the back of the tongue.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1077.","responses":[{"text":"Hyoglossus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatoglossus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pharyngoglossus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Styloglossus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Genioglossus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13022,"text":"The posterior arch of which cervical vertebra has a groove for the vertebral artery?","explanation":"The **posterior arch** of the **C1 vertebra**, also known as the atlas, has a groove for the passage of the vertebral artery. This is one of the unique features of the atlas that distinguishes it from the other cervical vertebrae.\r\n\r\nThe vertebral artery is an important blood vessel that supplies the posterior circulation of the brain. It ascends through the transverse foramen of the upper six cervical vertebrae, including C1. When it reaches the atlas, the vertebral artery enters the groove on the posterior arch of C1, known as the **vertebral artery groove**.\r\n\r\nThe presence of this groove in the posterior arch of C1 allows the vertebral artery to pass safely through the cervical vertebrae without being compressed or impinged upon. This arrangement protects the vertebral artery as it travels towards the skull, eventually joining the contralateral vertebral artery to form the basilar artery.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1021.","responses":[{"text":"C4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C1","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13023,"text":"Which of the following cervical vertebrae is atypical?","explanation":"The atypical cervical vertebra is **C7**, also known as the vertebra prominens.\r\n\r\nThe most notable feature of C7 is its **long spinous process**, which is not bifid like the spinous processes of the other cervical vertebrae. Instead, it is easily palpable and projects posteriorly, giving it a prominent appearance. This prominence can be felt at the base of the neck, hence the name \"vertebra prominens.\"\r\n\r\nAnother distinguishing feature of C7 is the absence of **costal facets** on its transverse processes. Costal facets are found on the transverse processes of the thoracic vertebrae and are involved in articulating with the ribs. Since C7 is the first vertebra without costal facets, it marks the transition from the cervical to the thoracic region of the spine.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 78.","responses":[{"text":"C4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C7","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13024,"text":"Which of the following features is not a characteristic of a typical cervical vertebra?","explanation":"A typical cervical vertebra possesses several distinguishing features. These include a **bifid spinous process** (except for the C7 vertebra, which has a non-bifid spinous process), a **triangular vertebral foramen**, **uncinate processes** on the body that contribute to the uncovertebral joints, and **foramina transversarium** located in the transverse processes.\r\n\r\nHowever, the presence of **costal facets** is not a characteristic of typical cervical vertebrae. Costal facets are articular surfaces found on the transverse processes of thoracic vertebrae and are associated with the articulation of ribs. Cervical vertebrae do not have costal facets because they do not articulate with ribs.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 78.","responses":[{"text":"Triangular vertebral foramen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Costal facets","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramina transversarium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bifid spinous process","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uncinate process on the body","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13025,"text":"Which of the following is bound by both the anterior and the posterior belly of the digastric muscle?","explanation":"The **digastric muscle** is a muscle located in the anterior triangle of the neck. It has two bellies, the anterior belly and the posterior belly, which are connected by an intermediate tendon. The anterior belly originates from the digastric fossa of the mandible, while the posterior belly originates from the mastoid notch of the temporal bone.\r\n\r\nThe **submandibular triangle** is a subdivision of the anterior triangle of the neck. It is bound by the inferior border of the mandible superiorly, the anterior and posterior bellies of the digastric muscle laterally, and the midline of the neck medially. The submandibular gland is located within this triangle.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 995.","responses":[{"text":"Submental triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscular triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carotid triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submandibular triangle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Omoclavicular triangle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13026,"text":"The anterior triangle of the neck is bound by which of the following posteriorly?","explanation":"The **anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle** forms the posterior boundary of the anterior triangle of the neck.\r\n\r\nThe sternocleidomastoid muscle is a prominent muscle located on each side of the neck. Its anterior border, along with the midline of the neck, helps define the boundaries of the anterior triangle. The anterior triangle is one of the divisions of the neck and is an important anatomical region for understanding the structures and structures within it.\r\n\r\nThe other boundaries of the anterior triangle include the **inferior border of the mandible** superiorly and the **anterior midline of the neck** inferiorly. Together, these boundaries delineate the triangular-shaped region known as the anterior triangle of the neck.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 989.","responses":[{"text":"Anterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior border of sternocleidomastoid muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior belly of omyhyoid muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior belly of digastric muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior belly of digastric muscle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13027,"text":"The two bellies of the digastric muscle have different embryological origins. What is true about the innervation of the muscle?","explanation":"The **digastric muscle** is a muscle of the neck that consists of two bellies: the **anterior belly** and the **posterior belly**. These two bellies have different embryological origins and are innervated by different branches of the trigeminal nerve.\r\n\r\nThe **anterior belly** of the digastric muscle is derived from the **first pharyngeal arch** during embryonic development. It is innervated by the **mandibular division (V3)** of the trigeminal nerve. V3 supplies motor innervation to the muscles of mastication, including the anterior belly of the digastric.\r\n\r\nThe **posterior belly** of the digastric muscle, on the other hand, is derived from the **second pharyngeal arch**. It is innervated by the **facial nerve (CN VII)**. The facial nerve carries motor fibers to the posterior belly, along with other muscles of facial expression.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 996.","responses":[{"text":"Posterior belly is innervated by V2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior belly is innervated by V1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior belly is innervated by V3","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior belly is innervated by V1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior belly is innervated by V2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13028,"text":"The pterygopalatine fossa communicates with the orbit through which of the following?","explanation":"The **inferior orbital fissure** is a narrow opening located at the lower part of the orbit, connecting the **pterygopalatine fossa** with the orbit.\r\n\r\nThe pterygopalatine fossa is a small space located deep within the skull, and it serves as a pathway for various structures, including nerves and blood vessels. It is situated posterior to the maxillary sinus and lateral to the nasal cavity.\r\n\r\nThe communication between the pterygopalatine fossa and the orbit through the inferior orbital fissure allows for the passage of structures such as the infraorbital nerve, which is a branch of the maxillary nerve (a branch of the trigeminal nerve). Additionally, blood vessels supplying the orbit may also traverse through this fissure.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 983.","responses":[{"text":"Pterygomaxillary fissure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterygoid canal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior orbital fissure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior orbital fissure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic canal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13037,"text":"The pterygopalatine fossa is bound anteriorly by which of the following?","explanation":"The **pterygopalatine fossa** is a small space located in the skull, and it is bound anteriorly by the **maxilla** bone. The maxilla forms the front part of the pterygopalatine fossa, separating it from the oral cavity.\r\n\r\nThe pterygopalatine fossa is a complex anatomical region that serves as a conduit for various structures, including nerves, blood vessels, and muscles. It is located deep within the skull, posterior to the maxillary sinus and lateral to the nasal cavity.\r\n\r\nUnderstanding the boundaries of the pterygopalatine fossa is important for surgical and clinical procedures involving the structures within this space. For example, the fossa provides passage for the maxillary nerve (a branch of the trigeminal nerve), as well as blood vessels supplying the nasal cavity and palate.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 982.","responses":[{"text":"Zygomatic process","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxilla","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasal bone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hard palate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13038,"text":"At what level is the isthmus of the thyroid gland present?","explanation":"The **isthmus of the thyroid gland** is a narrow band of tissue that connects the two lobes of the thyroid gland in the midline of the neck. It is located at the level of the **2nd, 3rd, and 4th tracheal rings**. \r\n\r\nThe tracheal rings are C-shaped cartilaginous rings that provide support and maintain the patency of the trachea. The isthmus of the thyroid gland lies anteriorly to the trachea and spans across these three tracheal rings.\r\n\r\nUnderstanding the level of the isthmus of the thyroid gland is important for clinical assessment and surgical procedures involving the thyroid gland. For example, during a thyroidectomy, the incision is typically made just above the sternal notch to allow access to the isthmus and thyroid lobes.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 1027.","responses":[{"text":"4th, 5th, and 6th tracheal rings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd, 4th, and 5th tracheal rings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1st, 2nd, and 3rd tracheal rings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oblique line of the thyroid cartilage till the 6th tracheal ring","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2nd, 3rd, and 4th tracheal rings","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13039,"text":"The sternocleidomastoid muscle divides the neck into which of the following?","explanation":"The sternocleidomastoid muscle, which runs diagonally across the neck, divides the neck into two main triangles: the **anterior triangle** and the **posterior triangle**.\r\n\r\n1. The **anterior triangle** is located anteriorly to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and is further divided into smaller triangles, including the **submental triangle** (located beneath the chin) and the **submandibular triangle** (located beneath the mandible).\r\n\r\n2. The **posterior triangle** is located posteriorly to the sternocleidomastoid muscle and is also divided into smaller triangles, including the **occipital triangle** (located at the base of the skull) and the **supraclavicular triangle** (located above the clavicle).\r\n\r\nThese triangles are clinically important for the identification and evaluation of structures within the neck, such as blood vessels, nerves, lymph nodes, and muscles.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 989.","responses":[{"text":"Submental and submandibular triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior and posterior triangles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Carotid and submandibular triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Submental and carotid triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supraclavicular and suboccipital triangle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13040,"text":"A patient developed winging of the scapula after deep cervical lymph node biopsy. Which nerve is involved?","explanation":"The **accessory spinal nerve** innervates the **trapezius muscle** and contributes to the movement and stability of the scapula. Damage or injury to the accessory spinal nerve can lead to weakness or paralysis of the trapezius muscle, resulting in winging of the scapula. This can cause difficulty in raising the arm and performing movements involving the shoulder girdle.\r\n\r\nAmong the other options listed, the **external laryngeal nerve** is responsible for innervating the cricothyroid muscle and is not involved in scapular movements. The **vagus nerve** and **glossopharyngeal nerve** have different functions primarily related to the autonomic innervation and sensory supply of various structures in the head and neck, but they do not directly innervate the trapezius muscle. The **recurrent laryngeal nerve** is responsible for innervating the muscles involved in vocal cord function and is not associated with scapular winging.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 1091.","responses":[{"text":"Accessory spinal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Recurrent laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13074,"text":"A surgeon noticed bleeding from the pharynx while removing adenoids from a 13-year-old child. Which artery supplies the pharynx?","explanation":"The **ascending pharyngeal artery** is a branch of the external carotid artery. It arises from the posterior aspect of the external carotid artery and ascends along the lateral wall of the pharynx. It provides vascular supply to the pharyngeal walls, tonsils, soft palate, and other structures in the pharyngeal region.\r\n\r\nDuring adenoidectomy, which involves the removal of the adenoid tissue from the nasopharynx, there is a risk of encountering the ascending pharyngeal artery due to its proximity to the surgical site. In the given scenario, the bleeding observed during the procedure suggests injury to the ascending pharyngeal artery, resulting in the bleeding from the pharynx.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1038.","responses":[{"text":"Inferior alveolar artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascending pharyngeal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Occipital artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13075,"text":"The second part of the maxillary artery travels between the heads of which muscle?","explanation":"The **maxillary artery** is one of the major branches of the external carotid artery. After its origin, it enters the infratemporal fossa and divides into three parts. The second part of the maxillary artery courses horizontally between the two heads of the **lateral pterygoid** muscle, which are the superior head and the inferior head.\r\n\r\nThe lateral pterygoid muscle is located deep within the infratemporal fossa and plays a crucial role in the movement of the mandible. It consists of two heads, and the maxillary artery passes between these heads as it continues its course. The artery gives off branches to supply various structures within the infratemporal fossa, including the deep temporal arteries and the buccal artery.\r\n\r\nUnderstanding the relationship between the maxillary artery and the lateral pterygoid muscle is important in surgical and dental procedures within the infratemporal region.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 979.","responses":[{"text":"Buccinator muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pterygoid muscle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Digastric muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Masseter muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial pterygoid muscle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13076,"text":"Which artery's main trunk is divided into mandibular, pterygoid, and pterygopalatine parts?","explanation":"The **maxillary artery** is one of the major branches of the external carotid artery. It arises deep within the parotid gland and has a tortuous course within the infratemporal fossa. As it travels through the infratemporal fossa, it gives off various branches that supply the structures within this region.\r\n\r\nThe maxillary artery has three main divisions or parts: the mandibular part, the pterygoid part, and the pterygopalatine part. The mandibular part gives rise to branches such as the deep auricular artery, anterior tympanic artery, and middle meningeal artery. The pterygoid part gives off branches like the masseteric artery and the deep temporal arteries. The pterygopalatine part supplies structures within the pterygopalatine fossa, including the posterior superior alveolar artery and the infraorbital artery.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 979.","responses":[{"text":"Superficial temporal artey","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Occipital artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior auricular artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13084,"text":"Which of the following is not a part of the deep cervical fascia?","explanation":"The **deep cervical fascia** is a complex system of connective tissue layers that provides support and compartmentalization within the neck region. It consists of several layers, each with distinct anatomical relationships and functions. The layers of the deep cervical fascia include the investing layer, pretracheal fascia, prevertebral fascia, and carotid sheath.\r\n\r\nThe **superficial fascia**, on the other hand, is a separate layer of connective tissue that lies beneath the skin and above the deep cervical fascia. It contains adipose tissue, blood vessels, and nerves, and its primary function is to provide insulation and support for the skin.\r\n\r\nWhile the deep cervical fascia plays important roles in separating and compartmentalizing structures within the neck, the superficial fascia is not considered part of this deeper fascial system.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 989.","responses":[{"text":"Pretracheal fascia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevertebral fascia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial fascia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Investing layer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carotid sheath","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13086,"text":"Which of the following structures pierces the buccinator muscle?","explanation":"The structure that pierces the buccinator muscle is the **parotid duct**, also known as **Stenson's duct**.\r\n\r\nThe parotid duct is a channel that carries saliva from the parotid gland to the oral cavity. It arises from the anterior part of the parotid gland and travels across the masseter muscle. As it reaches the buccinator muscle, it pierces through the muscle to enter the oral cavity. This allows the saliva produced by the parotid gland to be released into the mouth.\r\n\r\nThe buccinator muscle is a flat muscle located in the cheek region. It forms the majority of the cheek and is involved in actions such as compressing the cheek during chewing and helping with speech.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 923.","responses":[{"text":"Facial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Auriculotemporal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sublingual artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parotid or Stenson's duct","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep facial vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13089,"text":"Which nerve divides into branches in the parotid gland?","explanation":"The **facial nerve** is a mixed nerve that supplies motor innervation to the muscles of facial expression and also carries taste sensations from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue. Within the parotid gland, the facial nerve divides into several branches that innervate the muscles of facial expression.\r\n\r\nThese branches include the temporal, zygomatic, buccal, marginal mandibular, and cervical branches. They emerge from the main trunk of the facial nerve within the parotid gland and distribute to the specific muscles of the face.\r\n\r\nThe parotid gland is a salivary gland located in front of and below the ear. The facial nerve passes through the parotid gland, and its branches supply the muscles that control various facial expressions.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 901.","responses":[{"text":"Vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trigeminal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accessory nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13091,"text":"A 25-year-old presented to the emergency with stab wound in the neck at the submandibular triangle and tongue deviation. Which nerve is damaged?","explanation":"The **hypoglossal nerve** is responsible for the motor innervation of the muscles of the tongue. It provides motor control to the intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue, which are involved in its movement and positioning.\r\n\r\nDamage to the hypoglossal nerve can result in impaired function of the affected side of the tongue, leading to deviation of the tongue toward the injured side. This deviation occurs because the intact muscles on the opposite side of the tongue are unopposed by the paralyzed muscles on the injured side.\r\n\r\nThe hypoglossal nerve originates from the medulla oblongata in the brainstem and travels through the neck before innervating the tongue. Injuries in the submandibular triangle region can potentially damage the hypoglossal nerve, resulting in tongue deviation.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 957.","responses":[{"text":"Glossopharyngeal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trigeminal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accessory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoglossal","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13093,"text":"A surgeon wants to remove a benign swelling from the tip of the nose of a patient under local anesthesia. Which nerve is blocked to anesthise the external nose?","explanation":"The **ophthalmic nerve** is one of the three divisions of the trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V) and is responsible for providing sensory innervation to various regions of the face, including the external nose.\r\n\r\nThe ophthalmic nerve has multiple branches, one of which is the **nasociliary nerve**. The nasociliary nerve gives rise to the **external nasal branches**, which supply sensory innervation to the external surface of the nose.\r\n\r\nTo achieve local anesthesia of the external nose, the surgeon can perform a nerve block specifically targeting the nasociliary nerve or its external nasal branches. This can be achieved by injecting local anesthetic near the appropriate anatomical landmarks to block the sensory transmission from the ophthalmic nerve to the nose.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 934, 935.","responses":[{"text":"Infraorbital","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opthalamic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mandibular","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13096,"text":"A patient came to the otorhinolaryngologist with the complaint of difficulty opening the mouth. Diagnosis of infection of the infratemporal fossa was made. The muscle of mastication occupying most of the upper part of the fossa that helps in opening the mouth was affected. What is the affected muscle?","explanation":"The **lateral pterygoid** muscle is one of the muscles of mastication located in the infratemporal fossa. It plays a crucial role in the opening of the mouth by depressing and protracting the mandible.\r\n\r\nInfection of the infratemporal fossa can lead to inflammation and swelling, which can affect the function of the lateral pterygoid muscle and result in difficulty opening the mouth. This condition is known as trismus or lockjaw.\r\n\r\nThe lateral pterygoid muscle has two heads: the upper or superior head and the lower or inferior head. The superior head is involved in protraction of the mandible, while the inferior head assists in depression and lateral movement of the mandible. Dysfunction or inflammation of the lateral pterygoid muscle can lead to limited jaw movement and difficulty in opening the mouth.","reference":"(1) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 970, 972. (2) Casale J, Bordoni B. Anatomy, head and neck, infratemporal fossa. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 7, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537034/","responses":[{"text":"Buccinator","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Masseter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral pterygoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial pterygoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporalis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13097,"text":"The nerve that supplies the muscles of mastication and is a part of the infratemporal fossa passes through which foramen?","explanation":"The nerve that supplies the muscles of mastication and passes through the foramen located in the skull is the **mandibular nerve**, which is a branch of the trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V). The mandibular nerve carries sensory and motor fibers and is responsible for innervating the muscles of mastication, including the temporalis, masseter, medial pterygoid, and lateral pterygoid muscles.\r\n\r\nThe foramen through which the mandibular nerve passes is called the **foramen ovale**. It is located in the greater wing of the sphenoid bone, within the infratemporal fossa. The foramen ovale is an important anatomical landmark for the passage of several structures, including the mandibular nerve, the accessory meningeal artery, and some veins.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 973.","responses":[{"text":"Foramen stylomastoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramen ovale","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Emissary sphenoid foramen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramen lacerum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foramen rotundum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13098,"text":"The upper border of the mandible is thin and is surrounded by two processes; coronoid process anteriorly and condyloid process posteriorly. The two processes are separated by which deep cavity?","explanation":"The **mandibular notch** is a U-shaped indentation located between the coronoid and condyloid processes. It serves as a landmark for various structures and movements of the mandible. The coronoid process provides attachment for the temporalis muscle, which is involved in jaw closure and chewing. The condyloid process articulates with the mandibular fossa of the temporal bone, forming the temporomandibular joint (TMJ) and allowing for movements of the lower jaw.\r\n\r\nThe mandibular notch is an important anatomical feature to consider in various clinical scenarios, such as oral surgery, dental prosthetics, and TMJ disorders. Understanding the anatomy of the mandibular notch helps in accurate placement of dental implants, assessment of jaw movements, and management of conditions affecting the TMJ.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 963.","responses":[{"text":"Mandibular notch","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar process","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mental foramen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mandibular foramen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13099,"text":"What is the structure present on the anterior surface of the mandible through which inferior alveolar nerve and vessels pass called?","explanation":"The **mental foramen** is an opening located on the anterior surface of the mandible, typically situated in the region between the lower premolars. It provides an exit point for the mental nerve, a branch of the inferior alveolar nerve, as well as accompanying blood vessels. The mental nerve innervates the lower lip, chin, and mucous membranes of the lower lip and gingiva.\r\n\r\nThe mental foramen can vary in its exact location and may be present on one or both sides of the mandible. Its position can be important in clinical procedures, such as local anesthesia or dental implant placement, to avoid damage to the nerve and vessels passing through it.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1108.","responses":[{"text":"Mandibular foramen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mandibular notch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mental foramen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar process","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Condylar process","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13108,"text":"What is the dense fibrous connective tissue joint present between the frontal and the parietal bone called?","explanation":"The **coronal suture** is one of the major sutures of the skull, joining the frontal bone with the two parietal bones. It runs horizontally across the skull, extending from one temporal bone to the other. The term \"coronal\" refers to its position resembling a crown when viewed from above.\r\n\r\nDuring early development, the skull bones are separate, allowing for the growth and expansion of the brain. As the skull matures, the bones gradually fuse together at the sutures. The coronal suture is usually fully fused by adulthood, forming a strong connection between the frontal and parietal bones.\r\n\r\nThe coronal suture plays an important role in maintaining the stability and integrity of the skull. It provides strength and rigidity to the skull, protecting the underlying brain.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 846.","responses":[{"text":"Sagittal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coronal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphenofrontal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lambdoidal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13110,"text":"What is the thinnest part on the lateral wall of the skull where the anteroinferior corner of the parietal bone articulates with the greater wing of the sphenoid bone called?","explanation":"The **pterion** is a small, H-shaped area on the lateral aspect of the skull. It is formed by the articulation of four bones: the parietal, frontal, temporal, and greater wing of the sphenoid bone. The pterion is located approximately 2.5 cm above the midpoint of the zygomatic arch.\r\n\r\nThe significance of the pterion lies in the fact that it overlies the middle meningeal artery, a branch of the maxillary artery. This artery is vulnerable to injury at the pterion due to its proximity to the surface of the skull. Fractures or trauma to the pterion region can result in rupture of the middle meningeal artery, leading to an extradural hematoma.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 846.","responses":[{"text":"Pterion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Asterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supramastoid crest","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterygoid humulus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13111,"text":"What foramen is formed by the irregular medial end of the petrous part of the temporal bone, the greater wing of the sphenoid bone, and the basilar part of the occipital bone?","explanation":"The foramen formed by the irregular medial end of the petrous part of the temporal bone, the greater wing of the sphenoid bone, and the basilar part of the occipital bone is called the **foramen lacerum**.\r\n\r\nThe foramen lacerum is an important anatomical structure located in the base of the skull. Despite its name, it is not a true foramen but rather a gap filled with fibrous tissue. It is situated in the region where the petrous part of the temporal bone, the greater wing of the sphenoid bone, and the basilar part of the occipital bone meet.\r\n\r\nThe foramen lacerum is an important landmark in the skull, as it serves as a passageway for several structures, including the **internal carotid artery**, the **ascending pharyngeal artery**, and some **meningeal branches of the ascending pharyngeal artery**.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 851.","responses":[{"text":"Rotundum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lacerum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Jugular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ovale","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinosum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13114,"text":"Which artery supplies the maxillary sinus and the maxillary incisors?","explanation":"The artery that supplies the **maxillary sinus** and the **maxillary incisors** is the **infraorbital artery**.\r\n\r\nThe infraorbital artery is a branch of the **maxillary artery**, which is one of the main branches of the **external carotid artery**. After arising from the maxillary artery, the infraorbital artery courses through the **infraorbital canal** and emerges on the face through the **infraorbital foramen**.\r\n\r\nAs it emerges on the face, the infraorbital artery gives off branches that supply various structures, including the **maxillary sinus** (also known as the antrum of Highmore) and the **maxillary incisors**. These branches provide oxygenated blood to these structures, supporting their metabolic needs.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 988.","responses":[{"text":"Deep temporal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior superior alveolar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infraorbital","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pharyngeal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior alveolar","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13116,"text":"A 20-year-old male was brought to the emergency because of a wound on the scalp from a sharp object which was bleeding continuously. Bleeding from the scalp is always profuse due to what reason?","explanation":"The scalp is highly vascularized, and the blood vessels in the scalp lie just beneath the skin. When a sharp object causes a wound on the scalp, the blood vessels are cut, leading to bleeding. However, the profuse bleeding is not primarily due to the wound gape, the scalp's vascularity, or the presence of large arteries in the pericranium.\r\n\r\nThe key reason for profuse bleeding from the scalp is that the **vessel wall fails to retract**. The blood vessels in the scalp have a tendency to remain open and continue bleeding rather than constricting or retracting to reduce blood flow. This lack of vessel wall retraction contributes to the continuous bleeding observed in scalp injuries.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 911.","responses":[{"text":"Vessel wall fails to retract","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Wound gape","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scalp is highly vascular","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood vessels lie just beneath the skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large arteries lie in the pericranium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13118,"text":"Between which layers does the movement of the scalp take place?","explanation":"The movement of the scalp takes place between the **pericranium** and **loose areolar tissue**.\r\n\r\nThe scalp is the soft tissue covering the skull, and it is composed of several layers. The outermost layer is the **skin**, which is followed by a layer of **subcutaneous fat**. Beneath the subcutaneous fat, the scalp is formed by a dense, fibrous layer called the **epicranial aponeurosis**.\r\n\r\nDeep to the epicranial aponeurosis is the **loose areolar tissue**, which allows for movement between the layers. This loose areolar tissue provides mobility and allows for the scalp to be lifted or moved freely over the underlying structures.\r\n\r\nThe **pericranium**, which is the periosteum of the skull bones, is located deep to the loose areolar tissue. It is firmly attached to the underlying bone and does not participate in the movement of the scalp.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 912.","responses":[{"text":"Pericranium and epicranial aponeurosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin and subcutaneous fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericranium and loose areolar tissue","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin and epicranial aponeurosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericranium and skull","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13119,"text":"Which artery exits the middle cranial fossa through the optic canal?","explanation":"The artery that exits the middle cranial fossa through the optic canal is the **ophthalmic artery**.\r\n\r\nThe ophthalmic artery is a branch of the internal carotid artery and provides the main blood supply to the orbit and structures within the eye. It enters the orbit through the optic canal, which is a bony tunnel located in the lesser wing of the sphenoid bone.\r\n\r\nOnce inside the optic canal, the ophthalmic artery gives off several branches that supply various structures in the orbit and eye, including the retina, choroid, ciliary body, and iris. These branches contribute to the vascular supply and nourishment of the visual apparatus.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 923.","responses":[{"text":"Labyrinthine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle meningeal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep temporal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opthalamic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial temporal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13125,"text":"Which of the following describes the mucosa of the hard palate?","explanation":"The mucosa of the hard palate is **keratinized** and **lacks submucosa and minor salivary glands**.\r\n\r\nThe hard palate is the anterior portion of the roof of the mouth and is composed of both bone and mucous membrane. The mucosa covering the hard palate is specialized to withstand the mechanical stresses associated with mastication and speech.\r\n\r\nIn terms of its histological characteristics, the mucosa of the hard palate is **keratinized**, meaning it contains layers of keratinocytes that produce a protective protein called keratin. This keratinization provides the mucosa with increased durability and resistance to abrasion.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, the mucosa of the hard palate lacks **submucosa**, which is a layer of connective tissue found beneath the mucosa in other regions. Furthermore, it lacks **minor salivary glands**, which are small glands present in various locations of the oral cavity and produce saliva.","reference":"(1) Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 298. (2) Brizuela M, Winters R. Histology, oral mucosa. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 7, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK572115/","responses":[{"text":"Non-keratinized and has submucosa and minor salivary glands posteromedially","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Keratinized and has submucosa and minor salivary glands anteroinferiorly","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Keratinized and has submucosa and minor salivary glands posterolaterally","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Keratinized and lacks submucosa and minor salivary glands","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-keratinized and lacks submucosa and minor salivary glands","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13129,"text":"Which of the following is lined by small cuboidal cells in the duct system of the salivary glands?","explanation":"The duct system of the salivary glands consists of different types of ducts, each with its own epithelial lining. The duct lined by small cuboidal cells in the salivary gland duct system is the **intercalated duct**.\r\n\r\nThe intercalated duct is the smallest duct in the duct system and is located within the secretory units of the salivary glands. It receives the secretory product from the acini, which are the secretory units of the glands, and transports it towards larger ducts.\r\n\r\nThe epithelial lining of the intercalated duct is composed of small cuboidal cells. These cells are involved in modifying the composition of the saliva by reabsorbing certain ions and secreting bicarbonate ions.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 331.","responses":[{"text":"Intercalated duct","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interlobular duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intralobular duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Striated duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Main salivary duct","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13130,"text":"What is true regarding the sublingual salivary glands?","explanation":"The sublingual salivary glands are classified as **mixed glands**.\r\n\r\nSalivary glands are exocrine glands responsible for producing saliva, which helps in the initial stages of digestion and lubrication of the oral cavity. They can be classified based on the type of secretory cells they contain. These cells can be mucous cells, serous cells, or a combination of both.\r\n\r\nThe sublingual salivary glands, located beneath the tongue, are considered mixed glands. They consist of both **mucus-secreting cells** and **serous-secreting cells**. The mucus-secreting cells produce a thick and viscous mucus, while the serous-secreting cells produce a watery and enzyme-rich secretion.\r\n\r\nThe presence of both mucus-secreting and serous-secreting cells in the sublingual salivary glands allows them to secrete a mixture of mucus and enzymes, contributing to the lubrication and digestion of food.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 195.","responses":[{"text":"Minor gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucus gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed gland","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Present at the root of the tongue","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13131,"text":"The muscle that retracts the temporomandibular joint develops from which structure?","explanation":"The muscle that retracts the temporomandibular joint, known as the **temporalis muscle**, develops from the **1st pharyngeal arch**.\r\n\r\nDuring embryonic development, the pharyngeal arches play a crucial role in the formation of various structures in the head and neck region. The 1st pharyngeal arch, also known as the mandibular arch, gives rise to several important structures, including muscles, bones, and nerves involved in mastication and facial expression.\r\n\r\nThe temporalis muscle is one of the muscles derived from the 1st pharyngeal arch. It originates from the temporal fossa of the skull and inserts onto the coronoid process of the mandible. This muscle is responsible for retracting and elevating the mandible during the closing of the mouth.\r\n\r\nThe development of the temporalis muscle from the 1st pharyngeal arch highlights the complex interactions between neural crest cells, mesodermal tissues, and signaling pathways involved in the formation of the head and neck structures.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: \r\n160.","responses":[{"text":"2nd pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2nd pharyngeal arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd pharyngeal arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1st pharyngeal arch","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1st pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13134,"text":"What results from the failure of the fusion of maxillary prominence with the lateral nasal prominence?","explanation":"The failure of fusion between the maxillary prominence and the lateral nasal prominence during embryonic development can result in an **oblique facial cleft**.\r\n\r\nThe face develops from several facial prominences that fuse together to form the different structures of the face. The maxillary prominence is one of these prominences, and it contributes to the formation of the upper lip and the sides of the nose. The lateral nasal prominence is another facial prominence that contributes to the formation of the sides and tip of the nose.\r\n\r\nWhen there is a failure of fusion between the maxillary prominence and the lateral nasal prominence, an oblique facial cleft can occur. This cleft extends from the upper lip to the medial canthus of the eye, passing obliquely through the cheek.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: \r\n186.","responses":[{"text":"Median cleft lip","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unilateral oblique cleft lip","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cleft ovula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oblique facial cleft","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cleft palate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13137,"text":"The posterior one-third of the tongue develops from which of the following?","explanation":"The posterior one-third of the tongue develops from the **hypopharyngeal eminence**.\r\n\r\nDuring embryonic development, the tongue undergoes complex morphological changes as it forms from multiple tissue components. The hypopharyngeal eminence, also known as the third pharyngeal arch, contributes to the development of the posterior one-third of the tongue.\r\n\r\nThe hypopharyngeal eminence gives rise to a pair of lateral lingual swellings, which are bulges on the sides of the developing tongue. These lateral lingual swellings grow and merge with the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, which develop from the first pharyngeal arch.\r\n\r\nAs a result of the fusion between the lateral lingual swellings and the anterior tongue, the posterior one-third of the tongue is formed. This region of the tongue is primarily responsible for taste perception and is innervated by the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX).","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: \r\n172.","responses":[{"text":"Hypopharyngeal eminence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral lingual swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epiglottal swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculum impar","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13140,"text":"A patient visited an eye outpatient department with the complaint of loss of right field of vision in both eyes. Which of the following is damaged?","explanation":"In a patient presenting with the complaint of loss of the right field of vision in both eyes, the most likely site of damage is the **left optic tract**.\r\n\r\nVisual information from the right visual field of both eyes is processed by the left optic tract. The optic tract is a pathway that carries visual signals from the optic chiasm to the visual centers in the brain, including the primary visual cortex.\r\n\r\nAt the optic chiasm, the optic nerve fibers originating from the nasal (medial) side of each retina cross over to the opposite side. As a result, the left optic tract primarily carries information from the right visual field.\r\n\r\nIf there is damage to the left optic tract, it will result in a loss of the right field of vision in both eyes. This is known as a homonymous hemianopia, where vision loss occurs on the same side (homonymous) of both visual fields.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 349.","responses":[{"text":"Right optic tract","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left optic tract","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left optic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic chiasma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right optic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13141,"text":"The magnocellular layer of the lateral geniculate body is concerned with which visual information?","explanation":"The magnocellular layer of the lateral geniculate body is primarily concerned with **black-and-white vision**.\r\n\r\nThe lateral geniculate body is a relay station in the visual pathway located in the thalamus. It receives input from the optic tract and sends projections to the primary visual cortex.\r\n\r\nThe magnocellular layer, one of the layers within the lateral geniculate body, is specifically involved in processing certain aspects of visual information. It primarily receives input from the large, fast-conducting retinal ganglion cells known as magnocellular cells.\r\n\r\nThe magnocellular pathway is specialized for processing certain visual features, including motion, depth, and spatial information. It is particularly sensitive to low spatial frequencies and high temporal frequencies. This sensitivity allows for the perception of black-and-white vision and the detection of moving objects.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the parvocellular layer of the lateral geniculate body is responsible for processing color vision, fine details, and high spatial frequencies.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 654.","responses":[{"text":"Greater spacial resolution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower temporal resolution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Color vision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Black-and-white vision","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Discriminating fine details","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13143,"text":"A group of researchers wanted to identify substances which require charged ions for taste receptor stimulation. The charged ions can be a combination of which tastes?","explanation":"The substances that require charged ions for taste receptor stimulation can be a combination of **salty and sour** tastes.\r\n\r\nTaste perception is mediated by specialized taste receptor cells located on the taste buds of the tongue. These taste receptor cells detect different tastes, including sweet, salty, sour, bitter, and umami.\r\n\r\nSalty taste is primarily detected by taste receptor cells that are responsive to sodium ions (Na+). When substances containing salt come into contact with these taste receptors, the sodium ions bind to specific receptors, leading to the perception of a salty taste.\r\n\r\nSour taste, on the other hand, is perceived when substances with acidic properties, such as citric acid or acetic acid, come into contact with taste receptors. The acidity of these substances leads to the release of hydrogen ions (H+), which then interact with taste receptors, resulting in the perception of sourness.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 675.","responses":[{"text":"Bitter and sour","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salty and umami","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salty and sour","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sweet and sour","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sweet and umami","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13146,"text":"A high taste threshold in smokers is due to damage to which of the following?","explanation":"The high taste threshold observed in smokers is primarily due to **internal damage to papillae**.\r\n\r\nPapillae are small, nipple-like structures on the surface of the tongue that contain taste buds. Taste buds are clusters of specialized sensory cells responsible for detecting different tastes such as sweet, sour, salty, and bitter.\r\n\r\nIn smokers, the toxic components of cigarette smoke can cause damage to the delicate structures of the papillae and taste buds. This damage can result in a reduction in the number of functional taste buds and a decrease in their sensitivity to taste stimuli.\r\n\r\nAs a result, smokers often have a higher taste threshold, meaning they require stronger or more intense taste stimuli to perceive and appreciate flavors compared to non-smokers.","reference":"Khan AM, Narayanan VS, Puttabuddi JH, et al. Comparison of taste threshold in smokers and non-smokers using electrogustometry and fungiform papillae count: a case control study. Journal of Clinical and Diagnostic Research : JCDR. Published May 2016. Accessed December 8, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4948516/","responses":[{"text":"Taste center in cerebral cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nerve fibers carrying taste sensation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nucleus of tractus solitarius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal damage to papilla","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"External damage to taste buds","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13150,"text":"Which area of the cerebral cortex is responsible for the conscious perception, discrimination and analysis of odor?","explanation":"The area of the cerebral cortex that is responsible for the conscious perception, discrimination, and analysis of odor is the **orbitofrontal cortex**.\r\n\r\nThe orbitofrontal cortex is located in the frontal lobes of the cerebral cortex and is involved in various cognitive functions, including the processing of sensory information. In particular, it plays a crucial role in olfaction, or the sense of smell.\r\n\r\nWithin the orbitofrontal cortex, there are specialized neurons and circuits that receive input from the olfactory bulb and other brain regions involved in olfaction. These neurons integrate and analyze the sensory information related to odor perception.\r\n\r\nThe orbitofrontal cortex is responsible for the conscious perception and discrimination of different odors, allowing individuals to distinguish and identify various smells. It also plays a role in associating odor stimuli with emotional and behavioral responses.\r\n\r\nDamage or dysfunction of the orbitofrontal cortex can lead to impairments in odor perception, discrimination, and analysis, affecting an individual's ability to appreciate and interpret different smells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 682.","responses":[{"text":"Amygdala","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hippocampus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prepyriform cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orbitofrontal cortex","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13217,"text":"A patient lost his ability to smell. Which cells in his nasal mucosa were most likely damaged?","explanation":"**Bipolar cells** are a type of specialized sensory receptor cells located in the olfactory epithelium of the nasal cavity. These cells play a crucial role in the sense of smell or olfaction.\r\n\r\nThe olfactory system consists of olfactory receptor neurons, which are bipolar cells, and their olfactory cilia. These cells have specialized receptors on their surface that detect and respond to various odorants in the inhaled air.\r\n\r\nWhen an odorant molecule binds to the receptors on the olfactory cilia, it triggers a signal cascade that ultimately leads to the generation of nerve impulses. These impulses are transmitted to the olfactory bulb in the brain, where the processing and interpretation of smell occur.\r\n\r\nIf the bipolar cells in the nasal mucosa are damaged, the ability to detect and transmit smell signals to the brain is impaired, resulting in the loss of smell, also known as anosmia.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 679.","responses":[{"text":"Epithelial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multipolar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bipolar","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Unipolar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudo unipolar","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13218,"text":"Which center of the brain controls the rapid directional movement of the eyes?","explanation":"The **superior colliculus** is a paired structure located in the midbrain, specifically in the tectum of the mesencephalon. It plays a crucial role in the coordination and control of eye movements, particularly the rapid, voluntary movements of the eyes known as saccades.\r\n\r\nSaccadic eye movements are important for shifting the line of sight from one object or location to another. They are rapid, ballistic movements that allow for the exploration of the visual environment and precise focusing on specific targets of interest.\r\n\r\nThe superior colliculus receives visual input from the retina and integrates this information with input from other sensory modalities and higher brain centers. It then generates signals that initiate and direct the desired eye movements.\r\n\r\nOther brain structures mentioned, such as the suprachiasmatic nucleus of the hypothalamus, paraventricular nucleus of the hypothalamus, ventral lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus, and pretectal nuclei in the midbrain, are involved in various functions related to visual processing and control but do not specifically control rapid eye movements.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 652.","responses":[{"text":"Superior colliculus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Suprachiasmatic nucleus of the hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraventricular nucleus of the hypothalamus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pretectal nuclei in the midbrain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventral lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13219,"text":"A 35-year-old male presents to the clinic with a decrease in near vision while distant vision is normal. Retinoscopy at 1-meter shows that he requires spherical lens for the correction of vision. Which error of refraction is present in the patient?","explanation":"The most likely error of refraction present in the patient based on the clinical presentation is **hypermetropia**, also known as farsightedness.\r\n\r\nHypermetropia is a refractive error in which the eye's optical system focuses light rays behind the retina instead of directly on it. This occurs either because the eyeball is too short or the refractive power of the cornea and lens is insufficient.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the patient presents with a decrease in near vision while distant vision remains normal. This is a typical symptom of hypermetropia, as the eye has difficulty focusing on close objects.\r\n\r\nThe need for a **spherical lens** for correction during retinoscopy at a distance of 1 meter further supports the diagnosis of hypermetropia. The use of a convex (plus) lens helps to converge light rays onto the retina, allowing for clearer vision of nearby objects.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 632.","responses":[{"text":"Hypermetropia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Presbyopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accommodation paralysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Astigmatism","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13220,"text":"A child presents with difficulty in seeing the blackboard while sitting at the benches at the back in school. What is the most likely cause of his condition?","explanation":"**Myopia** is a refractive error in which the eye's optical system focuses light rays in front of the retina instead of directly on it. As a result, distant objects appear blurry, while close objects can be seen more clearly.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the child's complaint of difficulty in seeing distant objects, specifically the blackboard, suggests myopia. Myopia typically manifests during childhood or adolescence and can progressively worsen over time.\r\n\r\nThe child's difficulty in seeing distant objects while being able to see near objects clearly is a characteristic feature of myopia. This condition can be addressed by using corrective lenses such as eyeglasses or contact lenses with concave (minus) lenses. These lenses help to focus light rays further back onto the retina, enabling clearer vision for distant objects.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 632.","responses":[{"text":"Presbyopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypermetropia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Astigmatism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accommodation paralysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myopia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13221,"text":"Myopia is most commonly caused by an increase in which of the following?","explanation":"Myopia, commonly known as nearsightedness, is a refractive error of the eye that causes distant objects to appear blurry while close objects remain clear. It occurs when the eyeball is elongated, causing light rays to focus in front of the retina instead of directly on it.\r\n\r\nThe increase in the anteroposterior diameter of the eyeball is the primary factor contributing to myopia. When the eyeball becomes too long from front to back, the distance between the lens and the retina increases, causing the image to form in front of the retina rather than directly on it.\r\n\r\nOther factors, such as the shape of the cornea and lens, can also contribute to the development of myopia, but the elongation of the eyeball is the major underlying cause.\r\n\r\nMyopia can be corrected with eyeglasses, contact lenses, or refractive surgery, which adjust the focusing power of the eye to move the image back onto the retina.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 632.","responses":[{"text":"Thickness of the lens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anteroposterior diameter of the eyeball","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Viscosity of vitreous humor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thickness of the cornea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viscosity of aqueous humor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13222,"text":"A 44-year-old man visits his ophthalmologist with the complaint of increasing difficulty in reading the newspaper. His vision problem is due the inability to contract which of the following structures?","explanation":"The ability to focus on near objects is mediated by a process called accommodation, which involves the contraction of the ciliary body in the eye. This allows for the adjustment of the lens shape, increasing its curvature and refractive power to bring close objects into clear focus on the retina.\r\n\r\nIn the case of the 44-year-old man experiencing difficulty in reading, his vision problem is likely due to a decreased ability to accommodate, a condition known as presbyopia. Presbyopia is an age-related change that affects the flexibility and elasticity of the lens and makes it more difficult to focus on near objects.\r\n\r\nThe ciliary body, which is responsible for the contraction of the ciliary muscles, plays a crucial role in accommodation. When the ciliary muscles contract, the tension on the suspensory ligaments attached to the lens decreases, allowing the lens to become more convex and increase its refractive power.\r\n\r\nThe inability to contract the ciliary body effectively results in reduced accommodative ability and difficulty in focusing on near objects.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 631.","responses":[{"text":"Extraocular muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suspensory ligaments","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radial muscles of the iris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pupil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciliary body","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13223,"text":"Light energy activates rhodopsin which is a key process in phototransduction. What is the activated form of rhodopsin that excites electrical changes in the rods?","explanation":"In the process of phototransduction, light energy activates rhodopsin, which is the visual pigment found in the rod cells of the retina. Rhodopsin is composed of a protein called opsin and a light-absorbing molecule called 11-cis retinal.\r\n\r\nWhen rhodopsin absorbs a photon of light, it undergoes a conformational change, causing the 11-cis retinal to isomerize to its all-trans form. This conversion leads to the activation of rhodopsin, resulting in the formation of two forms: metarhodopsin-I (Meta-I) and metarhodopsin-II (Meta-II).\r\n\r\nMetarhodopsin-II is the fully activated form of rhodopsin that initiates the electrical changes in the rod cells. It activates a signaling cascade within the cell, leading to the closure of sodium channels and hyperpolarization of the rod cell membrane. This hyperpolarization is the electrical response that ultimately leads to the transmission of visual information to the brain.\r\n\r\nTherefore, metarhodopsin-II is the key intermediate in the process of phototransduction that excites electrical changes in the rods.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 642.","responses":[{"text":"Metarhodopsin-II","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"11-trans retinal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bathorhodopsin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metarhodopsin-I","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lumirhodopsin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13225,"text":"A 54-year-old man was operated for neuronal tumor at the base of the brain. He complained of visual field defect postoperatively. Brain MRI showed lesion in the right optic tract. Which visual field defect is present in the patient?","explanation":"In this case, the patient has a lesion in the right optic tract, which results in a visual field defect on the contralateral side. The optic tracts carry visual information from the contralateral visual field of both eyes.\r\n\r\nA left homonymous hemianopia is characterized by a loss of vision in the left half of the visual field in both eyes. It occurs when there is a lesion affecting the right optic tract, which carries visual information from the right half of the visual field.\r\n\r\nIn the case described, the lesion in the right optic tract leads to a loss of vision in the left half of the visual field in both eyes. The patient will have difficulty seeing objects located in the left visual field.\r\n\r\nOther visual field defects, such as binasal hemianopia (loss of vision in the nasal halves of the visual fields), bitemporal hemianopia (loss of vision in the outer halves of the visual fields), and right homonymous hemianopia (loss of vision in the right half of the visual field in both eyes), are not consistent with the given information.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 349.","responses":[{"text":"Binasal hemianopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right homonymous hemianopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left homonymous hemianopia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bitemporal hemianopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left sided anopia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13226,"text":"A second year MBBS student performed experiments related to the sense of taste in the physiology lab. Which of the following taste sensation will have the lowest stimulation threshold?","explanation":"Among the five primary taste sensations (sweet, sour, salty, bitter, and umami), bitter taste sensation has the lowest stimulation threshold. This means that bitter substances can be detected at lower concentrations compared to other taste sensations.\r\n\r\nBitter taste receptors are typically more sensitive and can recognize a wide range of bitter compounds. This heightened sensitivity to bitterness is thought to have evolved as a protective mechanism against the ingestion of potentially toxic substances, as many bitter compounds are associated with toxicity in nature.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, other taste sensations such as sweet, sour, salty, and umami have higher stimulation thresholds and require higher concentrations of specific substances to be perceived. Sweet taste is typically associated with sugars, sour taste with acidic substances, salty taste with the presence of ions, and umami taste with savory or protein-rich foods.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that individual variations in taste sensitivity can exist, and different individuals may have different thresholds for detecting specific taste sensations.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 676.","responses":[{"text":"Sour","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bitter","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sweet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salty","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13227,"text":"Rhodopsin is a conjugated protein present in the rods of the retina. What is its composition?","explanation":"Rhodopsin is a visual pigment found in the rods of the retina. It is composed of two main components: opsin and 11-cis-retinal.\r\n\r\nOpsin is a protein that belongs to the G-protein coupled receptor (GPCR) family. It forms the structural backbone of rhodopsin and plays a crucial role in the activation of the visual signaling pathway. Opsin undergoes conformational changes upon absorption of light, leading to the activation of downstream signaling molecules.\r\n\r\n11-cis-retinal is a chromophore that is derived from vitamin A. It is a light-sensitive molecule that is covalently bound to opsin. When light enters the retina and interacts with 11-cis-retinal, it undergoes isomerization to its all-trans form. This triggers a cascade of events that ultimately leads to the generation of electrical signals in the rod cells and the initiation of the visual perception process.\r\n\r\nTogether, opsin and 11-cis-retinal form the functional unit of rhodopsin, allowing for the detection and transduction of light signals in the visual system.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 388.","responses":[{"text":"Opsin and retinoic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Keratin and 11-cis-retinal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crystalline and retinoic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Crystalline and 11-cis-retinal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opsin and 11-cis-retinal","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13228,"text":"Most infants are born with which of the following?","explanation":"Hypermetropia, also known as farsightedness, is the most common refractive error found in infants at birth. It is a condition in which the eyeball is shorter than normal or the refractive power of the eye is weaker, causing difficulty in focusing on nearby objects.\r\n\r\nIn infants, the eye undergoes significant growth and development during the first few years of life. At birth, the eyeball is relatively small, and the focusing mechanism of the eye is not fully matured. As a result, many infants exhibit hypermetropia, which tends to decrease as the eye grows and the focusing ability improves.\r\n\r\nHypermetropia in infants is often referred to as physiological hypermetropia, as it is considered a normal part of the developmental process. With time, as the eye grows and the refractive power becomes more balanced, most infants outgrow their hypermetropia and achieve normal visual acuity.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that not all infants will have hypermetropia, and some may exhibit other refractive errors such as myopia or astigmatism. Regular eye examinations by a pediatric ophthalmologist are recommended to monitor and address any visual abnormalities in infants.","reference":"Varghese RM, Sreenivas V, Puliyel JM, Varughese S. Refractive status at birth: its relation to newborn physical parameters at birth and gestational age. PLoS ONE. Published February 13, 2009. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2636866/","responses":[{"text":"Emmetropia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amblyopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Astigmatism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypermetropia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13231,"text":"The five broad personality traits described by theory are extraversion, agreeableness, openness, conscientiousness, and neuroticism. Personality evaluation of Ali indicates that he has the tendency to be responsible, hard-working, goal-directed, organized and to adhere to norms and rules. Based on the findings, Ali must have scored high on which scale of big five personality test?","explanation":"Conscientiousness is one of the five broad personality traits described by the Big Five personality theory. It refers to the tendency to be responsible, organized, hard-working, goal-directed, and to adhere to norms and rules. Individuals who score high on conscientiousness are generally reliable, self-disciplined, and focused on achieving their goals.\r\n\r\nBased on the description provided, Ali demonstrates characteristics that align with high conscientiousness. His tendency to be responsible, hard-working, goal-directed, organized, and adherence to norms and rules indicates a conscientious personality trait. Individuals high in conscientiousness are often diligent in their work, have strong organizational skills, and are committed to meeting their responsibilities and obligations.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that the Big Five personality traits are measured on a continuum, and individuals may exhibit a range of scores on each trait. However, the description provided suggests that Ali's personality aligns more strongly with the conscientiousness trait.","reference":"Lim AGY. [big five personality traits]. https://www.simplypsychology.org/big-five-personality.html. Published online 2020. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://www.simplypsychology.org/big-five-personality.html","responses":[{"text":"Agreeableness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extraversion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Openness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neuroticism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Conscientiousness","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15789,"text":"Which of the following muscles forms the roof of the suboccipital triangle of the neck?","explanation":"The muscle that forms the roof of the suboccipital triangle of the neck is the **Semispinalis capitis**. The suboccipital triangle is a small region located at the back of the neck, beneath the occiput. It is primarily involved in the movements and stabilization of the head.\r\n\r\nThe boundaries of the suboccipital triangle are:\r\n- Medially: Rectus capitis posterior major\r\n- Inferolaterally: Obliquus capitis inferior\r\n- Superolaterally: Obliquus capitis superior\r\n\r\nThe roof of this triangle is formed by the semispinalis capitis muscle, a large muscle that extends from the transverse processes of the upper thoracic and lower cervical vertebrae to the occipital bone. The semispinalis capitis is overlaid by the dense, fibrous connective tissue of the nuchal fascia, and it plays a significant role in extending and rotating the head.","reference":"George T, Tadi P. Anatomy, head and neck, suboccipital muscles. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed May 14, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK567762/","responses":[{"text":"Rectus capitis posterior minor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Semispinalis capitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Obliquus capitis inferior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rectus capitis posterior major","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obliquus capitis superior","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15790,"text":"The duct of the largest salivary gland, which forms a major part of salivary secretions, opens into which of the following regions of the oral cavity?","explanation":"The duct of the largest salivary gland, the **parotid gland**, opens into the oral cavity opposite to the **second maxillary molar tooth**.\r\n\r\nThe parotid gland is located in front of the ear, and its main duct, called **Stensen's duct**, passes through the cheek and opens into the oral cavity. Specifically, it opens into the oral cavity opposite to the second upper molar tooth. This is commonly referred to as the **parotid papilla** or **parotid duct orifice**.\r\n\r\nSaliva produced by the parotid gland contains enzymes, electrolytes, and mucus, and it plays an important role in lubricating the oral cavity, initiating digestion, and maintaining oral health.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 923.","responses":[{"text":"Caruncula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Side of the lingual frenulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Floor of the mouth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opposite to second maxillary molar tooth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sublingual fossa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15791,"text":"The pharyngeal plexus lies on which of the following muscles of the pharynx?","explanation":"The **pharyngeal plexus** is located on the **middle pharyngeal constrictor muscle**.\r\n\r\nThe pharyngeal plexus is a network of nerves formed by branches from the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX), vagus nerve (CN X), and sympathetic fibers. It innervates the muscles of the pharynx, including the superior, middle, and inferior pharyngeal constrictor muscles, as well as other structures in the pharyngeal wall.\r\n\r\nThe middle pharyngeal constrictor muscle is located in the middle layer of the pharyngeal wall. It forms part of the posterior pharyngeal wall and contributes to swallowing and narrowing of the pharynx during swallowing.","reference":"Halliday NL, M C Harold, Won C Kyung. BRS: Gross Anatomy. 10th ed. Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2020: 410.","responses":[{"text":"Superior pharyngeal constrictor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salpingopharyngeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stylopharyngeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle pharyngeal constrictor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior pharyngeal constrictor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15792,"text":"Which of the following cervical vertebrae has an odontoid process?","explanation":"The **second cervical vertebra (C2)**, also known as the axis, has an **odontoid process** (also called the dens). The odontoid process is a bony projection that extends superiorly from the body of C2 and acts as a pivot point for the rotation of the atlas (C1) and the skull.\r\n\r\nThe odontoid process articulates with the anterior arch of the atlas, forming a joint known as the **atlantoaxial joint**. This joint allows for the rotation of the head and neck.\r\n\r\nThe presence of the odontoid process in C2 distinguishes it from the other cervical vertebrae. The remaining cervical vertebrae (C1, C3-C7) do not have this unique feature.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 993.","responses":[{"text":"C2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C1","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15793,"text":"A 44-year-old male patient presents to the outpatient clinic with a progressive loss of temporal field of vision. Visual field testing confirms bitemporal hemianopia. When compressed, which of the following structures is most likely to result in this defect?","explanation":"The **optic chiasma** is the anatomical structure located at the base of the brain where the optic nerves partially cross over. It is formed by the convergence of the optic nerves from each eye. The fibers carrying nasal visual field information cross over at the optic chiasma, while the fibers carrying temporal visual field information continue straight back without crossing.\r\n\r\nCompression or lesion of the optic chiasma can lead to visual field defects known as **bitemporal hemianopia**. In this condition, there is loss of the temporal visual field in both eyes, resulting in a characteristic \"tunnel vision\" appearance. The compression typically affects the crossing nasal fibers, leading to loss of peripheral vision on both sides.\r\n\r\nCommon causes of optic chiasma compression include **pituitary adenomas** and other tumors located in the region of the sella turcica.","reference":"Splittgerber R, Snell RS. Snell’s Clinical Neuroanatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2019: 349.","responses":[{"text":"Visual cortex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic chiasma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic tract","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic radiations","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15794,"text":"Which of the following types of receptors is the taste receptor characterized as?","explanation":"Taste receptors are specialized sensory receptors located on the taste buds of the tongue and other regions of the oral cavity. They are responsible for detecting and transducing the sense of taste. Taste receptors are categorized as **chemoreceptors** because they respond to specific chemical substances dissolved in saliva.\r\n\r\nChemoreceptors are sensory receptors that detect changes in chemical composition. They are involved in the perception of taste, smell, and chemical changes in the internal environment. Taste receptors are specifically sensitive to various taste stimuli, such as sweet, salty, sour, bitter, and umami (savory).\r\n\r\nThe taste receptor cells are activated when specific molecules bind to taste receptor proteins on their surface, leading to the generation of electrical signals that are transmitted to the brain, resulting in the perception of taste.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 675.","responses":[{"text":"Osmoreceptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mechanoreceptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Baroreceptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pacinian corpuscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemoreceptor","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15795,"text":"A 32-year-old male patient presents to the outpatient clinic with the complaint of excessive droopiness of the left eyelid (ptosis). Loss of function of which of the following muscles can result in this condition?","explanation":"Ptosis, or drooping of the eyelid, can occur due to the loss of function of the **levator palpebrae superioris** muscle. The levator palpebrae superioris muscle is responsible for elevating the upper eyelid.\r\n\r\nThe levator palpebrae superioris muscle is innervated by the oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III). The nerve fibers from the oculomotor nucleus travel through the superior orbital fissure and reach the levator muscle, where they stimulate its contraction. Damage or dysfunction of the oculomotor nerve can result in weakness or paralysis of the levator palpebrae superioris muscle, leading to ptosis.\r\n\r\nPtosis can cause functional and cosmetic issues for the patient, as it may affect their visual field and overall appearance. Treatment options for ptosis depend on the underlying cause and may include surgical intervention to repair or strengthen the muscle, or the use of supportive measures such as eyelid crutches or ptosis props.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 919.","responses":[{"text":"Orbicularis oculi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Levator palpebrae superioris","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior rectus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15797,"text":"A soldier hears the sound of gunshots and follows in the direction of the sound. Which of the following structures is responsible for the detection of the direction from which the sound is coming?","explanation":"The **lateral superior olivary nucleus** is responsible for detecting the direction of sound. It plays a crucial role in sound localization in the auditory system.\r\n\r\nWhen a sound reaches the ears, it reaches one ear slightly before the other. The brain compares the time and intensity differences between the two ears to determine the direction from which the sound is coming. The lateral superior olivary nucleus receives input from both ears and analyzes these differences.\r\n\r\nThe neurons in the lateral superior olivary nucleus integrate the information from both ears and generate an output that helps determine the direction of the sound source. This information is further processed and refined in higher centers of the auditory pathway.\r\n\r\nDamage or dysfunction of the lateral superior olivary nucleus can lead to difficulties in sound localization and may result in auditory processing disorders.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 672.","responses":[{"text":"Lateral superior olivary nucleus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cochlear nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior colliculus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial superior olivary nucleus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral geniculate body","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15798,"text":"Which of the following arteries is located in the suboccipital triangle?","explanation":"The **third part of the vertebral artery** is located in the suboccipital triangle.\r\n\r\nThe suboccipital triangle is a small triangular area located on the posterior aspect of the neck, bounded by the rectus capitis posterior major, obliquus capitis superior, and obliquus capitis inferior muscles. Within this triangle, the third part of the vertebral artery passes through.\r\n\r\nThe vertebral artery is one of the major arteries that supply blood to the brain. It arises from the subclavian artery and ascends through the transverse foramina of the cervical vertebrae. After entering the suboccipital triangle, the third part of the vertebral artery gives off branches to supply the muscles and structures in the area.\r\n\r\nWhile other arteries, such as the occipital artery, posterior auricular artery, and suboccipital artery, may also be in close proximity to the suboccipital triangle, the third part of the vertebral artery is specifically associated with this anatomical region.","reference":"George T, Tadi P. Anatomy, head and neck, suboccipital muscles. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed May 14, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK567762/","responses":[{"text":"Third part of vertebral artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Suboccipital artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Occipital artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior auricular artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Third part of basilar artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15799,"text":"A 59-year-old male patient presents to the ophthalmology clinic with a complaint of double vision. On evaluation, it is found that the muscle responsible for lateral rotation of the eye is paralyzed. Which of the following nerves innervates this muscle?","explanation":"The muscle responsible for lateral rotation of the eye is the **lateral rectus muscle**. It is innervated by the **abducens nerve** (cranial nerve VI). The abducens nerve supplies motor fibers to the lateral rectus muscle, which controls abduction of the eye, allowing it to move laterally away from the midline.\r\n\r\nIn the case of a paralyzed lateral rectus muscle, the patient experiences difficulty in moving the affected eye laterally, resulting in double vision (diplopia). This is because the unopposed action of the medial rectus muscle, innervated by the oculomotor nerve (cranial nerve III), causes inward deviation of the affected eye.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 908.","responses":[{"text":"Trochlear nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trigeminal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abducens nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oculomotor nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15806,"text":"A school counselor observes a student who works really hard and is highly ambitious toward his goal, but he can be very competitive and self-critical. In certain situations, he also tends to be impatient and shows anger management issues. Which of the following personality types is this student most likely to have?","explanation":"Type A personality is characterized by a set of behavioral and psychological traits that include competitiveness, ambition, impatience, a sense of urgency, and a tendency to be self-critical. Individuals with Type A personality traits are often highly motivated, hardworking, and driven to achieve their goals. They may also exhibit anger management issues and be prone to experiencing stress.\r\n\r\nType A personality was initially described in relation to coronary heart disease, as individuals with this personality type were found to have a higher risk of developing cardiovascular problems due to the chronic stress associated with their behavioral patterns. However, it is important to note that Type A personality is not a formal psychiatric diagnosis but rather a descriptive term used to describe certain personality traits and behavior patterns.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Head and Neck and Special Senses module. Subject: Behavioral sciences. Topic: Personality, Subtopic: Type A behavior.","responses":[{"text":"Type B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type D","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type A","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Type C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type E","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15808,"text":"Which of the following landmarks in the skull of an adult marks the location of the posterior fontanelle in neonates?","explanation":"The landmark in the skull of an adult that marks the location of the posterior fontanelle in neonates is the **lambda**.\r\n\r\nThe lambda is a point on the skull where the sagittal suture (which separates the two parietal bones) meets the lambdoid suture (which separates the parietal bones from the occipital bone). In neonates, this region is represented by the posterior fontanelle, which is a membranous space between the parietal and occipital bones. As the skull bones gradually fuse during development, the fontanelles close, and the posterior fontanelle is eventually replaced by the lambda in adults.\r\n\r\nThe other options—pterion, nasion, bregma, and asterion—refer to different anatomical landmarks on the skull but do not correspond to the location of the posterior fontanelle in neonates.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 849.","responses":[{"text":"Asterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lambda","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bregma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pterion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15810,"text":"Which of the following types of glands are the major salivary glands categorized under?","explanation":"The major salivary glands are categorized as **compound tubuloacinar glands**.\r\n\r\nCompound glands have a branching duct system, and tubuloacinar glands have both tubular and acinar components. The major salivary glands, which include the parotid, submandibular, and sublingual glands, have complex duct systems that consist of both tubular and acinar structures.\r\n\r\nIn the salivary glands, the acinar cells are responsible for producing and secreting saliva, while the ducts transport and modify the saliva before it is released into the oral cavity. The tubular components of the glands are involved in the modification of saliva, such as reabsorption and secretion of specific ions.\r\n\r\nThe other options—simple tubuloacinar glands, compound acinar gland, simple acinar glands, and compound tubular glands—do not accurately describe the structure and organization of the major salivary glands.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 191.","responses":[{"text":"Simple tubuloacinar glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Compound acinar gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Compound tubular glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple acinar glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Compound tubuloacinar glands","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15829,"text":"The maxillary artery which is embedded in the parotid gland supplies the deep tissue of the face. It is a terminal branch of which of the following arteries?","explanation":"The maxillary artery, which supplies the deep tissues of the face, is a terminal branch of the **external carotid artery**.\r\n\r\nThe external carotid artery is one of the two main branches of the common carotid artery. It supplies blood to the structures of the face, scalp, and neck. As it ascends in the neck, the external carotid artery gives rise to several branches, one of which is the maxillary artery.\r\n\r\nThe maxillary artery enters the parotid gland and gives off multiple branches that supply various structures in the deep face, including the muscles, bones, and teeth. It continues its course to supply other regions, such as the pterygopalatine fossa, nasal cavity, and oral cavity.\r\n\r\nThe other options—facial artery, subclavian artery, vertebral artery, and internal carotid artery—are not directly related to the origin of the maxillary artery.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 901.","responses":[{"text":"Facial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vertebral artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External carotid artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subclavian artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15830,"text":"Pituitary adenomas can result in compression of the pituitary stalk. Which of the following is the most likely indication of compression of the pituitary stalk?","explanation":"Compression of the pituitary stalk, which connects the hypothalamus to the pituitary gland, can lead to **hyperprolactinemia**.\r\n\r\nThe pituitary gland secretes several hormones, including prolactin. Prolactin is responsible for stimulating milk production in the mammary glands. Under normal conditions, the release of prolactin is regulated by dopamine, which inhibits its secretion. However, compression of the pituitary stalk can disrupt the flow of dopamine from the hypothalamus to the pituitary gland, leading to increased secretion of prolactin. This condition is known as hyperprolactinemia.\r\n\r\nHyperprolactinemia can result in various symptoms, such as galactorrhea (spontaneous milk production), menstrual irregularities, infertility, and sexual dysfunction.","reference":"Zaidi HA, Cote DJ, Castlen JP, et al. Time course of resolution of hyperprolactinemia after transsphenoidal surgery among patients presenting with pituitary stalk compression. World Neurosurgery. Published January 2017. Accessed May 15, 2023. https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1878875016308968","responses":[{"text":"Headache","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased serum ADH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vomiting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Memory loss","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperprolactinemia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15831,"text":"The superior oblique muscle is supplied by which of the following cranial nerves?","explanation":"The **trochlear nerve** (cranial nerve IV) supplies the superior oblique muscle of the eye.\r\n\r\nThe superior oblique muscle is responsible for intorsion (inward rotation), depression, and abduction of the eyeball. It originates from the common tendinous ring within the orbit and passes through a fibrous loop called the trochlea, located at the superomedial aspect of the orbit. The trochlear nerve enters the orbit and innervates the superior oblique muscle by supplying its motor fibers.\r\n\r\nThe other options—superior branch of oculomotor nerve, inferior branch of oculomotor nerve, optic nerve, and abducens nerve—do not innervate the superior oblique muscle.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 908.","responses":[{"text":"Abducens nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior branch of oculomotor nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trochlear nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Optic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior branch of oculomotor nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15832,"text":"Which of the following nerves supplies the anterior wall of the external acoustic meatus?","explanation":"The **auriculotemporal nerve** supplies the anterior wall of the external acoustic meatus.\r\n\r\nThe auriculotemporal nerve is a branch of the mandibular division (V3) of the trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V). It arises near the middle meningeal artery and courses upward and backward deep to the superficial temporal artery. It carries sensory fibers from the skin of the temple, external ear, and anterior wall of the external acoustic meatus.\r\n\r\nThe greater auricular nerve supplies sensory innervation to the skin over the parotid gland and the angle of the mandible. The lesser occipital nerve supplies sensory innervation to the skin of the posterior scalp. The glossopharyngeal nerve and auricular branch of the vagus nerve are not directly involved in supplying the anterior wall of the external acoustic meatus.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 975.","responses":[{"text":"Greater auricular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lesser occipital nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Auriculotemporal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Auricular branch of vagus nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15841,"text":"Which of the following muscles of facial expression is involved in smiling?","explanation":"The **zygomaticus major** muscle is involved in smiling.\r\n\r\nThe zygomaticus major is one of the muscles of facial expression located in the cheek region. It originates from the zygomatic bone (cheekbone) and inserts into the corner of the mouth. When the zygomaticus major contracts, it pulls the corner of the mouth upward and laterally, resulting in the characteristic upward movement seen during smiling.\r\n\r\nThe levator labii superioris and levator anguli oris muscles are involved in lifting the upper lip and elevating the angle of the mouth, respectively. The corrugator supercilii muscle is responsible for vertical wrinkling of the forehead, often associated with frowning or expressing worry. The risorius muscle retracts the angle of the mouth laterally.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 854.","responses":[{"text":"Levator labi superioris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Risorius","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zygomaticus major","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Levator anguli oris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corrugator supercilii","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15842,"text":"The philtrum of the upper lip is derived from which of the following embryological structures?","explanation":"The **philtrum of the upper lip** is derived from the fusion of the **medial nasal prominence** and the **maxillary prominence** during embryological development.\r\n\r\nDuring early embryogenesis, the face develops from a series of facial prominences that grow and fuse together. The medial nasal prominence gives rise to the middle part of the upper lip, including the philtrum. The maxillary prominence contributes to the lateral parts of the upper lip.\r\n\r\nThe fusion of the medial nasal prominence and the maxillary prominence forms the upper lip and defines its characteristic features, including the philtrum, which is the vertical groove in the center of the upper lip.\r\n\r\nThe other options—the lateral nasal prominence and medial nasal prominence, frontonasal prominence and maxillary prominence, maxillary prominence only, and maxillary prominence and lateral nasal prominence—do not accurately represent the embryological origin of the philtrum.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 178.","responses":[{"text":"Frontonasal prominence and maxillary prominence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary prominence and lateral nasal prominence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral nasal prominence and medial nasal prominence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial nasal prominence and maxillary prominence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary prominence only","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15843,"text":"A 36-year-old male patient presents to the outpatient clinic with an infection of the nasal and paranasal sinuses. He complains of a headache and vision problems. A CT scan reveals cavernous sinus thrombosis. Which of the following veins is the most likely route of spread of infection from the area around the nose and upper lips to the cavernous sinus?","explanation":"**Explanation:**\r\nThe cavernous sinus is a dural venous sinus located on each side of the sella turcica in the skull base. It receives blood from various veins, including the superior ophthalmic vein.\r\n\r\nThe superior ophthalmic vein drains blood from the structures around the eyes, including the forehead, scalp, and upper face. It communicates with the cavernous sinus and provides a potential pathway for the spread of infection from the area around the nose and upper lips to the cavernous sinus.\r\n\r\nIn cases of sinusitis or infection in the nasal and paranasal sinuses, the infection can spread through valveless veins, such as the superior ophthalmic vein, leading to cavernous sinus thrombosis.\r\n\r\nThe other veins listed—the infraorbital vein, supraorbital vein, supratrochlear vein, and inferior ophthalmic vein—do not provide a direct route of spread from the nasal and paranasal sinuses to the cavernous sinus.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 883.","responses":[{"text":"Supraorbital vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior ophthalmic vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior ophthalmic vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infraorbital vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supratrochlear vein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15844,"text":"A greater palatine nerve block will anesthetize which of the following areas of the oral cavity?","explanation":"A **greater palatine nerve block** is a regional anesthesia technique used to anesthetize specific areas of the oral cavity. It involves targeting the greater palatine nerve, a branch of the maxillary nerve (V2).\r\n\r\nWhen a greater palatine nerve block is performed, it anesthetizes the **palatal mucosa** (roof of the mouth) and the **lingual gingivae** (gums on the inner side) posterior to the **maxillary canine teeth**.\r\n\r\nThe greater palatine nerve travels through the greater palatine foramen, which is located in the posterior part of the hard palate. By injecting local anesthetic near the greater palatine foramen, the nerve can be effectively blocked, resulting in anesthesia of the specified areas.\r\n\r\nThe other options—the buccal gingivae of molars, buccal gingivae of premolars, palatine mucosa only, and palatal mucosa and lingual gingivae anterior to maxillary canine teeth—are not typically anesthetized by a greater palatine nerve block.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 957.","responses":[{"text":"Buccal gingivae of molars","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatal mucosa and lingual gingivae anterior to maxillary canine teeth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatal mucosa and lingual gingivae posterior to maxillary canine teeth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatine mucosa only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccal gingivae of premolars","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15845,"text":"Which of the following layers of the scalps contains the blood vessels supplying the scalp?","explanation":"The **connective tissue layer** of the scalp contains the blood vessels supplying the scalp.\r\n\r\nThe scalp is composed of five layers, which can be remembered using the mnemonic \"SCALP\":\r\n1. **S**kin: The outermost layer of the scalp.\r\n2. **C**onnective tissue: This layer contains the blood vessels, nerves, and lymphatics that supply the scalp.\r\n3. **A**poneurosis (Epicranial aponeurosis): Also known as the galea aponeurotica, it is a broad, flat, tendon-like structure that connects the frontalis and occipitalis muscles.\r\n4. **L**oose areolar connective tissue: This layer provides mobility between the scalp and the underlying structures.\r\n5. **P**eriosteum (Pericranium): The innermost layer of the scalp, which covers the outer surface of the skull bones.\r\n\r\nThe blood vessels supplying the scalp, including the superficial temporal artery and vein, are located within the connective tissue layer. These vessels provide the necessary blood supply for nourishment and oxygenation of the scalp tissues.\r\n\r\nThe other options—the loose areolar connective tissue, pericranium, epicranial aponeurosis, and skin—are not primarily responsible for containing the blood vessels supplying the scalp.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 863.","responses":[{"text":"Pericranium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epicranial aponeurosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loose areolar connective tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Connective tissue","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15848,"text":"Congenital aphakia results when an important structure of the eye fails to develop. Which of the following embryonic layers does this structure originate from?","explanation":"Congenital aphakia refers to the absence or failure of development of the lens in the eye. The lens is an important structure of the eye that plays a crucial role in focusing light onto the retina.\r\n\r\nDuring embryonic development, the lens of the eye originates from the **surface ectoderm**, which is the outermost layer of the developing embryo.\r\n\r\nIn the early stages of eye development, a thickening called the **optic vesicle** forms from the neuroectoderm. The surface ectoderm overlying the optic vesicle invaginates to form a **lens placode**, which subsequently undergoes further changes to form a lens vesicle.\r\n\r\nThe lens vesicle differentiates into the **primary lens fibers** that constitute the bulk of the lens. These primary lens fibers are derived from the surface ectoderm and eventually give rise to the mature lens.\r\n\r\nThe other options—the mesoderm, endoderm, neuroectoderm, and paraxial mesoderm—do not give rise to the lens structure during embryonic development.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 417, 426.","responses":[{"text":"Endoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neuroectoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surface ectoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraxial mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15849,"text":"Which of the following layers of the cornea does not have the ability to regenerate once damaged?","explanation":"Among the layers of the cornea, **Bowman's membrane** does not have the ability to regenerate once damaged.\r\n\r\nThe cornea is the transparent, outermost layer of the eye that covers the iris, pupil, and anterior chamber. It consists of five layers: corneal epithelium, Bowman's membrane, corneal stroma, Descemet's membrane, and corneal endothelium.\r\n\r\nBowman's membrane is a **non-regenerative acellular layer** located between the corneal epithelium and the corneal stroma. It is composed of dense collagen fibers and provides structural support to the cornea.\r\n\r\nUnlike other layers of the cornea, Bowman's membrane lacks regenerative capacity. If it is damaged or removed, it cannot regenerate or repair itself naturally. Once damaged, the defect in Bowman's membrane often persists, and it can lead to corneal irregularities or scarring.\r\n\r\nThe other layers of the cornea—the corneal epithelium, corneal stroma, Descemet's membrane, and corneal endothelium—have varying degrees of regenerative capacity and can undergo repair or regeneration after injury or damage.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 243.","responses":[{"text":"Descemet's membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corneal stroma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bowman's membrane","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Corneal endothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corneal epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15851,"text":"Which of the following is the primary function of the superior oblique?","explanation":"The **primary function** of the **superior oblique muscle** is **intorsion** of the eye.\r\n\r\nIntorsion refers to the rotational movement of the eye inwards or medially. When the superior oblique muscle contracts, it causes the upper part of the eye to rotate medially, or inwards, around the anteroposterior axis.\r\n\r\nThe superior oblique muscle is located within the orbit of the eye and arises from the upper part of the medial wall. Its tendon passes through the trochlea, a fibrocartilaginous structure, and attaches to the sclera (white part) of the eye.\r\n\r\nIn addition to its primary function of intorsion, the superior oblique muscle also contributes to other movements of the eye, including depression (downward movement) and abduction (outward movement) when acting in conjunction with other eye muscles.\r\n\r\nThe other options—abduction, adduction, extorsion, and depression—are not the primary function of the superior oblique muscle.","reference":"Abdelhady A, Patel BC, Aslam S, Al Aboud DM. Anatomy, head and neck: eye superior oblique muscle. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed May 16, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537152/","responses":[{"text":"Depression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Extorsion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intorsion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15860,"text":"The cells of the thyroid gland, which secrete calcitonin, are derived from which of the following embryological structures?","explanation":"The cells of the thyroid gland that secrete **calcitonin** are derived from the **ultimobranchial body**, which is an embryological structure.\r\n\r\nDuring embryonic development, the thyroid gland originates from two distinct structures: the **thyroid diverticulum** and the **ultimobranchial body**. The thyroid diverticulum arises from the **endoderm** of the **pharyngeal floor**, while the ultimobranchial body originates from **neural crest cells**.\r\n\r\nThe ultimobranchial body migrates and fuses with the thyroid diverticulum to contribute to the development of the **parafollicular cells**, also known as **C cells**, within the thyroid gland. These C cells are responsible for producing and secreting the hormone calcitonin.\r\n\r\nCalcitonin is involved in calcium homeostasis and plays a role in regulating bone metabolism.\r\n\r\nThe other options—the second pharyngeal cleft, second pharyngeal pouch, fourth pharyngeal cleft, and first pharyngeal pouch—are not directly involved in the development of the cells that secrete calcitonin.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2016: 163,164.","responses":[{"text":"Second pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultimobranchial body","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Second pharyngeal cleft","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fourth pharyngeal cleft","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"First pharyngeal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15862,"text":"A child is brought to the emergency room with an injury to the nasal septum. Which of the following bones are most likely to be affected?","explanation":"When a child sustains an injury to the nasal septum, the most likely bones to be affected are the **perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone** and the **vomer**.\r\n\r\nThe nasal septum divides the nasal cavity into left and right sides and is composed of several structures, including the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone and the vomer. The perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone forms the superior portion of the nasal septum, while the vomer forms the inferior and posterior part.\r\n\r\nInjuries to the nasal septum can occur due to trauma, such as a direct blow to the nose. The force applied during the injury can cause displacement, fracture, or damage to the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone and the vomer.\r\n\r\nWhile other bones, such as the nasal bones or maxillary bones, can also be affected in nasal injuries, the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid and the vomer are the most commonly involved bones in injuries specifically affecting the nasal septum.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 963.","responses":[{"text":"Nasal bones only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cribriform plate of ethmoid and vomer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perpendicular plate of ethmoid and vomer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary and nasal bones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasal and frontal bones","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15863,"text":"Which of the following is the correct term for age-related hearing loss?","explanation":"The correct term for age-related hearing loss is **presbycusis**.\r\n\r\nPresbycusis is a gradual, progressive sensorineural hearing loss that occurs with advancing age. It is the most common cause of hearing impairment in older adults. The exact underlying mechanisms of presbycusis are not fully understood, but it is believed to involve a combination of genetic factors, cumulative noise exposure, and age-related changes in the structures of the inner ear.\r\n\r\nPresbycusis typically affects high-frequency sounds first, making it difficult to hear and understand speech in noisy environments. Individuals with presbycusis may experience difficulty discriminating sounds, understanding conversations, and hearing high-pitched tones.\r\n\r\nOther options:\r\n\r\n- **Hyperacusis** refers to an increased sensitivity to sound.\r\n- **Hypoacusis** refers to a general decrease in hearing ability.\r\n- **Otosclerosis** is a condition characterized by abnormal bone growth in the middle ear, leading to progressive hearing loss.\r\n- **Presbyopia** is a condition of age-related loss of near vision due to changes in the flexibility of the lens.","reference":"Cheslock M, De Jesus O. Presbycusis. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed May 18, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559220/","responses":[{"text":"Hypoacusis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Otosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presbyopia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperacusis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presbycusis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15864,"text":"A child suffers from a lesion of the nasociliary ganglion. Which of the following nerves supplies the preganglionic parasympathetic fibers to this ganglion?","explanation":"The nerve that supplies the **preganglionic parasympathetic fibers to the nasociliary ganglion** is the **oculomotor nerve** (cranial nerve III).\r\n\r\nThe oculomotor nerve is responsible for innervating several muscles of the eye, including the levator palpebrae superioris, superior rectus, medial rectus, inferior rectus, and inferior oblique muscles. In addition to these motor fibers, the oculomotor nerve also carries parasympathetic preganglionic fibers that synapse in the ciliary ganglion.\r\n\r\nFrom the ciliary ganglion, postganglionic fibers distribute to various structures, including the pupillary sphincter muscle of the iris and the ciliary muscle. These structures are involved in controlling the diameter of the pupil and the shape of the lens, respectively.\r\n\r\nThe nasociliary ganglion is a small parasympathetic ganglion located within the orbit. It receives preganglionic parasympathetic fibers from the oculomotor nerve via a branch called the **short ciliary nerve**.\r\n\r\nWhile the short ciliary nerve provides sensory innervation to the eye, it does not supply the preganglionic parasympathetic fibers to the nasociliary ganglion.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 932, 933.","responses":[{"text":"Nerve to inferior oblique","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short ciliary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oculomotor nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trochlear nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasociliary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15865,"text":"Which of the following arteries is a terminal branch of the right common carotid artery?","explanation":"The **internal carotid artery** is the terminal branch of the right common carotid artery.\r\n\r\nThe common carotid artery is a major vessel that arises from the brachiocephalic trunk on the right side and directly from the aortic arch on the left side. It ascends in the neck and divides into two branches: the internal carotid artery and the external carotid artery.\r\n\r\nThe internal carotid artery continues its course through the neck without giving off any branches in the neck region. It enters the skull through the carotid canal of the temporal bone, reaching the cranial cavity. Inside the skull, the internal carotid artery gives rise to important branches, including the ophthalmic artery, anterior cerebral artery, middle cerebral artery, and posterior communicating artery.\r\n\r\nThe other listed options—maxillary artery, facial artery, ascending pharyngeal artery, and superior thyroid artery—are branches of the external carotid artery, not the internal carotid artery.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 999.","responses":[{"text":"Ascending pharyngeal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior thyroid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maxillary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal carotid artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15866,"text":"Which of the following muscles of the larynx is involved in the abduction of the vocal cords?","explanation":"The muscle of the larynx that is primarily involved in the **abduction of the vocal cords** is the **posterior cricoarytenoid muscle**.\r\n\r\nThe vocal cords (also known as vocal folds) are located within the larynx and play a crucial role in phonation and voice production. During normal respiration, the vocal cords are open and abducted, allowing the passage of air through the larynx and into the lower respiratory tract.\r\n\r\nThe **posterior cricoarytenoid muscle** is the only muscle in the larynx that acts to **abduct** the vocal cords. When this muscle contracts, it moves the arytenoid cartilages posteriorly and laterally, causing the vocal cords to move apart and open.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the other muscles mentioned—transverse arytenoid, vocalis, cricothyroid, and lateral cricoarytenoid—are involved in various functions of the vocal cords, such as adduction, tension adjustment, and phonation, but not specifically in the abduction of the vocal cords.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1050.","responses":[{"text":"Cricothyroid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vocalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transverse arytenoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior cricoarytenoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral cricoarytenoid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15867,"text":"Which of the following nerves supplies preganglionic parasympathetic nerve fibers to the otic ganglion?","explanation":"The nerve that supplies **preganglionic parasympathetic nerve fibers to the otic ganglion** is the **glossopharyngeal nerve** (cranial nerve IX).\r\n\r\nThe otic ganglion is a small parasympathetic ganglion located near the middle ear. It receives preganglionic parasympathetic fibers from the glossopharyngeal nerve.\r\n\r\nThe preganglionic parasympathetic fibers arise from the inferior salivatory nucleus in the medulla and travel with the glossopharyngeal nerve. These fibers then leave the glossopharyngeal nerve via a branch known as the **tympanic nerve**.\r\n\r\nThe tympanic nerve enters the middle ear cavity through the tympanic canaliculus and forms a small plexus of nerves called the tympanic plexus. From the tympanic plexus, postganglionic parasympathetic fibers reach the otic ganglion.\r\n\r\nThe other listed options—short ciliary nerve, chorda tympani, auricotemporal nerve, and nasociliary nerve—are not directly involved in supplying the preganglionic parasympathetic fibers to the otic ganglion.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 924.","responses":[{"text":"Nasociliary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Short ciliary nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chorda tympani","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glossopharyngeal nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Auricutemporal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15868,"text":"Which of the following disorders requires surgical removal?","explanation":"Among the listed disorders, the condition that typically requires **surgical removal** is an **acoustic neuroma**, also known as a vestibular schwannoma.\r\n\r\nAn acoustic neuroma is a benign tumor that arises from the Schwann cells of the vestibular (balance) nerve in the inner ear. It usually grows slowly and can cause symptoms such as hearing loss, tinnitus (ringing in the ears), vertigo, and imbalance.\r\n\r\nThe treatment options for acoustic neuroma depend on various factors, including the size of the tumor, the patient's age and overall health, and the severity of symptoms. Surgical removal, known as **translabyrinthine or retrosigmoid resection**, is often recommended for larger tumors or cases where the tumor is causing significant symptoms or impairing the patient's quality of life.\r\n\r\nMeningitis, presbycusis (age-related hearing loss), otitis media (middle ear infection), and hyperacusis (sensitivity to sound) may be managed with non-surgical approaches, such as medication, supportive care, or other conservative treatments..","reference":"Greene J, Al-Dhahir MA. Acoustic neuroma. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed May 19, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470177/","responses":[{"text":"Acoustic neuroma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperacusis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Otitis media","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Presbycusis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15869,"text":"The pulse of the facial artery can be palpated over the anteroinferior angle of which of the following muscles?","explanation":"The pulse of the **facial artery** can be palpated over the **anteroinferior angle of the masseter muscle**.\r\n\r\nThe facial artery is a branch of the external carotid artery that supplies blood to the structures of the face. It follows a tortuous course along the anterior border of the masseter muscle, a large muscle responsible for jaw movement.\r\n\r\nTo palpate the pulse of the facial artery, you can place your fingers over the anteroinferior angle of the masseter muscle, which is located in the lower part of the cheek region, just in front of the earlobe. Applying gentle pressure in this area can help identify the pulsation of the facial artery.\r\n\r\nThe other muscles listed—buccinator, orbicularis oris, temporalis, and zygomaticus major—are not directly associated with the location where the pulse of the facial artery can be palpated.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 906.","responses":[{"text":"Masseter","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Buccinator","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Temporalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orbicularis oris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zygomaticus major","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15870,"text":"Which of the following vessels is most commonly involved in the setting of an epidural hematoma?","explanation":"In the setting of an **epidural hematoma**, the **middle meningeal artery** is the vessel most commonly involved.\r\n\r\nAn epidural hematoma is an accumulation of blood between the dura mater (outermost layer of the meninges) and the inner surface of the skull. It is typically caused by trauma that results in rupture of the middle meningeal artery, which is a branch of the maxillary artery.\r\n\r\nThe middle meningeal artery runs in the epidural space, which is the potential space between the dura mater and the skull. In cases of severe head injury or skull fracture, the rupture of the middle meningeal artery can lead to bleeding into the epidural space, resulting in the formation of an epidural hematoma.\r\n\r\nThe other vessels listed—the anterior meningeal artery, dural venous sinus, emissary veins, and posterior meningeal artery—are less commonly associated with epidural hematomas compared to the middle meningeal artery.","reference":"Khairat A, Waseem M. Epidural hematoma. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed May 19, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK518982/","responses":[{"text":"Emissary veins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle meningeal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior meningeal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dural venous sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior meningeal artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15871,"text":"Which of the following arteries is most likely to be damaged in an injury to the subclavian triangle of the neck?","explanation":"Injury to the subclavian triangle of the neck is most likely to damage the **third part of the subclavian artery**.\r\n\r\nThe subclavian triangle, also known as the omoclavicular triangle or the posterior triangle of the neck, is a region bounded by the clavicle, the sternocleidomastoid muscle, and the omohyoid muscle. It contains important structures such as the subclavian artery, subclavian vein, and brachial plexus.\r\n\r\nThe third part of the subclavian artery is located within the subclavian triangle. This segment of the subclavian artery lies posterior to the anterior scalene muscle. Injuries to this area, such as fractures or penetrating trauma, can potentially damage the subclavian artery, leading to hemorrhage and compromised blood flow to the upper limb.\r\n\r\nThe other listed arteries—the ascending pharyngeal artery, external carotid artery, facial artery, and third part of the vertebral artery—are not specifically located within the subclavian triangle and are less likely to be involved in injuries to this region.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 999.","responses":[{"text":"External carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascending pharyngeal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Third part of subclavian artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Third part of vertebral artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facial artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15872,"text":"The hyoid bone develops from which of the following embryological structures?","explanation":"The hyoid bone develops from the **second and third pharyngeal arches** during embryological development.\r\n\r\nDuring early embryogenesis, the pharyngeal arches play a crucial role in the development of various structures in the head and neck region. The second and third pharyngeal arches contribute to the formation of the hyoid bone.\r\n\r\nThe second pharyngeal arch gives rise to the **greater horn** and the **lower part** of the body of the hyoid bone. These structures form the posterior portion of the hyoid bone.\r\n\r\nThe third pharyngeal arch contributes to the development of the **lesser horn** and the **upper part** of the body of the hyoid bone. These structures form the anterior portion of the hyoid bone.\r\n\r\nThe hyoid bone is a U-shaped bone located in the neck, just below the mandible. It serves as an attachment site for various muscles involved in swallowing, speech, and neck movement.\r\n\r\nThe other options—the fourth and sixth pharyngeal arches, first and second pharyngeal arches, and second and third pharyngeal pouches—do not accurately represent the embryological origin of the hyoid bone.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 285.","responses":[{"text":"First and second pharyngeal arches","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"First and second pharyngeal pouches","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fourth and sixth pharyngeal arches","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Second and third pharyngeal arches","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Second and third pharyngeal pouches","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15873,"text":"Which of the following correctly describes the sensory innervation of the superior laryngeal nerve?","explanation":"The **superior laryngeal nerve** provides sensory innervation to the **larynx above the vocal cords**.\r\n\r\nThe superior laryngeal nerve is a branch of the vagus nerve (cranial nerve X) and is divided into two branches: the internal branch and the external branch.\r\n\r\nThe **internal branch** of the superior laryngeal nerve supplies sensory fibers to the mucosa of the larynx above the vocal cords, including the epiglottis, aryepiglottic folds, arytenoids, and the region near the inlet of the larynx.\r\n\r\nThe **external branch** of the superior laryngeal nerve is primarily responsible for supplying motor innervation to the cricothyroid muscle, which helps control vocal cord tension.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that the internal branch of the superior laryngeal nerve carries sensory information from the upper part of the larynx, while the vocal cords themselves are innervated by the recurrent laryngeal nerve.\r\n\r\nThe other options—the larynx below the vocal cords, vocal cords only, anterior wall of the larynx, and posterior wall of the larynx—do not accurately describe the sensory innervation provided by the superior laryngeal nerve.","reference":"Soriano RM, Winters R, Gupta V. Anatomy, head and neck: larynx nerves. StatPearls. Published 2023. Accessed May 20, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557742/","responses":[{"text":"Larynx below the vocal cords","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vocal cords only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior wall of larynx","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior wall of larynx","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Larynx above the vocal cords","correct":true,"visible":false}]}
]

